Annotations.content:
Annotations is a powerful way of adding features to components, structs and classes.
The primary candidate for this feature are components and was originally made for components, hence why most annotations you’ll find are component-centric.
All annotations can found inside Source\Engine\Annotations.

Some systems provide an annotation within their own folder or module. For example, the tag system provides a tag container annotation and it can be found in Source\Engine\Tags

Usage
For a component to use annotations, simply call REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS.
struct [[Reflect]] MyComponent
{
    float MyFloat = 20;

    CATALYST_COMPONENT(MyComponent)

    REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS
    {
    }
};
You then use ADD_ANNOTATION to provide the item with annotations.
For example, this provides MyComponent with an editor icon and a constructor:
struct [[Reflect]] MyComponent
{
    float MyFloat = 20;

    CATALYST_COMPONENT(MyComponent)

    REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS
    {
        ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::EditorIcon{ &quot;Icons/Test.png&quot; });
        ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::ConstructorAnnotation {
            [](void* Ptr) {
                auto* Comp = static_cast&lt;MyComponent*&gt;(Ptr);
                Comp-&gt;MyFloat = 500.0f;
            }
        });
    }
};
You can then fetch annotations like so;
EditorIcon* Icon = AnnotationRegistry::Get().GetAnnotation&lt;EditorIcon, MyComponent&gt;()
External annotation modification
Annotations can be added or overwritten during runtime externally through something like a plugin. But it is recommended to only do this during the modules initialization.
//TODO Create example
See Also

Components — the primary consumer of annotations

Asset-Manager.content:
Alchemy Asset Manager
The Asset Manager is the engine’s central hub for loading, saving, and managing binary data. It provides a high-performance, version-aware serialization system that ensures data integrity and type safety across all engine modules.

Quick Start: The Basics
At its simplest, the Asset Manager allows you to load and save EntityLibrary objects (which act as containers for your game data) and most other types of assets, such as textures.
Loading an Asset
AssetManager* AM = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;AssetManager&gt;();
EntityLibrary* MyLevel = AM-&gt;LoadAsset(&quot;Content/Maps/Level01.alchemyasset&quot;);
Saving an Asset
AM-&gt;SaveAsset(&quot;Content/Maps/Level01.alchemyasset&quot;, *MyLevel);

Creating Reflectable Assets
To make a custom C++ struct saveable as an asset, simply mark it with the [[Reflect]] attribute. The Alchemy Reflector will automatically generate the necessary binary serialization code.
struct [[Reflect]] MyGameData
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(MyGameData)

    float Difficulty = 1.0f;
    Alchemy::String LevelName;
    Alchemy::Array&lt;int&gt; EnemyIDs;
};
Note: All fields are serialized by default. Use [[Transient]] to skip fields that shouldn’t be saved (like runtime-only timers or pointers).

Technical Architecture: Under the Hood
As you move deeper into the engine, the Asset Manager provides “Industry Grade” features to prevent crashes and data corruption.
1. The Asset Header
Every .alchemyasset file begins with a standardized header:

























FieldPurposeMagicA 4-byte signature (ALCH) to verify the file is a valid Alchemy asset.Engine VersionThe Major.Minor.Patch version of the engine that saved the file.Type HashA unique ID for the data type (e.g., EntityLibrary vs. Texture).Asset VersionA custom version number for that specific asset’s format.
2. Type Safety via Compile-Time Hashing
To prevent you from accidentally loading a Texture file into an Animation struct, the engine uses GetTypeHash&lt;T&gt;().
This is a consteval function that generates a unique 32-bit ID based on the compiler’s function signature. If the TypeHash in the file header doesn’t match the TypeHash of the class you are trying to load, the Asset Manager will stop and log an error before any data is parsed.
3. Versioning &amp; Backward Compatibility
The engine tracks two types of versions:

Engine Version: Global format changes (e.g., changing how Alchemy::String is stored).
Asset Version: Changes to a specific system (e.g., adding a new field to all EntityLibrary assets).

When loading, you can check these versions inside your serialization logic to “fix up” old data:
void Serialize(Archive&amp; Ar, MyData&amp; Data)
{
    Ar &amp; Data.BasicField;

    if (Ar.GetAssetVersion() &gt;= 2) {
        Ar &amp; Data.NewFieldAddedInVersion2;
    }
}
4. The Binary Archive
Unlike JSON or XML, Alchemy uses a custom binary Archive.

Speed: Data is bit-streamed directly from disk to memory.
POD Optimization: The Archive detects “Trivially Copyable” types (like int, float, or structs of primitives) and performs a single memcpy for the entire block rather than iterating field-by-field.
Mode Awareness: The same operator&amp; logic is used for both Saving and Loading, reducing code duplication and human error.


Asynchronous Loading
For production environments where hundreds of assets must be loaded without hitching the game thread, the Asset Manager provides a non-blocking AsyncLoadAsset method.
Usage
AssetManager* AM = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;AssetManager&gt;();

AM-&gt;AsyncLoadAsset(&quot;Content/Characters/Hero.alchemyasset&quot;, [](EntityLibrary* LoadedLib)
   {
    if (LoadedLib) {
        Log(&quot;Hero asset is ready to use!&quot;);
        // Add to world, spawn entities, etc.
    }
});
Key Features of Async Loading:

Job System Integration: Loading tasks (File IO + Deserialization) are dispatched to the JobSubsystem and run on background worker threads.
Request Deduplication: If five different systems request the same asset at the same time, the Asset Manager will only perform one disk read. All five callbacks will be queued and executed once the single load operation completes.
Thread Safety: While the data is loaded in the background, the completion callbacks are automatically dispatched back to the Main Thread, ensuring you can safely modify game state or spawn entities in response to an asset being loaded.


Batch Asynchronous Loading
When loading large sets of assets (e.g., streaming in a new world region), using individual AsyncLoadAsset calls in a loop can hitch the game thread due to job dispatch overhead. To solve this, the Asset Manager provides BatchAsyncLoadAssets.
Usage
AssetManager* AM = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;AssetManager&gt;();
Array&lt;String&gt; LevelPaths = { &quot;Cell_0_0.alchemyasset&quot;, &quot;Cell_0_1.alchemyasset&quot;, ... };

AM-&gt;BatchAsyncLoadAssets(LevelPaths, [](const Array&lt;EntityLibrary*&gt;&amp; LoadedLibs)
{
    Log(&quot;All 50 world cells have been loaded in parallel!&quot;);
    for (EntityLibrary* Lib : LoadedLibs)
    {
        // Process batch
    }
});
Why Use Batching?

Reduced Dispatch Overhead: Instead of hitting the job system 50 times for 50 assets, the batch system uses ParallelForBatch to submit the entire workload in a single “wave.” This keeps the game thread 100% smooth even when requesting hundreds of assets.
The “Wave Strategy”: The system processes assets in small chunks (e.g., 5-10 at a time per worker thread). This staggers the OS-level file opening calls, preventing the “Thundering Herd” effect where too many simultaneous disk requests actually slow down the overall throughput.
Instruction Locality: Because worker threads process multiple assets in a tight loop, the CPU stays in the “Deserialization” instruction path longer, improving cache efficiency.

See Also

Catalyst — EntityLibrary, the data container assets are loaded into
Jobs — the job system used for async and batch asset loading

Catalyst/Components.content:
A component is a pure data structure tied to an entity. In the ECP architecture, components should ideally contain no logic, acting only as state containers for Processors to transform.
Declaration
To define a component, create a standard C++ struct, mark it with the [[Reflect]] attribute, inherit from CatalystComponent, and use the CATALYST_COMPONENT macro. The [[Reflect]] attribute registers the type with the reflection system, the base struct declares the component’s storage policy, and the macro provides the compile-time type name used for lookups.
struct [[Reflect]] HealthComponent : Alchemy::CatalystComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(HealthComponent)

    float CurrentHealth = 100.0f;
    float MaxHealth = 100.0f;
};
Every Catalyst data type inherits exactly one storage-policy base struct, and that choice is fixed for the type’s lifetime:




















Base structStored inAdd / remove costCatalystComponentthe entity’s archetypestructural — migrates the entity to a new archetypeCatalystSparseComponenta side table keyed by entitynon-structural — no archetype change
CatalystComponent is the default and what you should reach for first. Use CatalystSparseComponent for data that is toggled frequently or only lives on a small fraction of entities — see Sparse Components. The closely related presence-only flags (CatalystMarker / CatalystSparseMarker) follow the same pattern and are covered in Tags and Markers.



                  Components must never declare virtual methods. 



A component is stored and relocated as raw bytes — memcpy’d between archetype chunks, bulk-copied from prefabs, and serialized field by field. A vtable pointer would be copied verbatim and silently corrupt all of that. The storage-policy base struct is the only inheritance a component needs; otherwise keep them plain data. The library static_asserts that components are non-polymorphic.


Usage in Code
Components are managed by the EntityLibrary. You can add, retrieve, or remove them using templated methods.
// Adding a component
Library.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity, { .CurrentHealth = 50.0f });

// Retrieving a component (returns nullptr if not found)
HealthComponent* Health = Library.GetComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Removing a component
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);
Short form via EntityRef
When you have an EntityRef instead of a bare handle — for example from Library.CreateEntity(),
Library.Ref(Handle), or a query parameter — the same operations read shorter, because the entity
already carries its library:
EntityRef Entity = Library.CreateEntity();

Entity.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;({ .CurrentHealth = 50.0f });
HealthComponent* Health = Entity.GetComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;();
Entity.RemoveComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;();
EntityRef mirrors every per-entity method shown on this page and is foolproof (it can never resolve
against the wrong library). It is zero-cost in optimized builds. See EntityRef for the full picture.
Component Slots
Component Slots allow a single entity to have multiple instances of the same component type, each identified by a unique slot name. This is essential for scenarios like NPCs with multiple mesh components (body, weapon, armor) that need to remain cache-efficient.
Basic Usage
Use the overloaded AddComponent and GetComponent methods that accept a slot name:
// Adding slotted components
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, bodyMesh, &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, armorMesh, &quot;Armor&quot;);

// Retrieving a specific slot
MeshComponent* Weapon = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Get all slots as an iterable span
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; AllMeshes = Library.GetComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
for (const auto&amp; Entry : AllMeshes)
{
    ProcessMesh(Entry.Component, Entry.SlotID);
}

// Count slots
uint32_t SlotCount = Library.GetSlotCount&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Remove a specific slot
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
The slot overloads are mirrored on EntityRef, so the same setup reads more directly when you hold a ref:
EntityRef Entity = Library.CreateEntity();
Entity.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(bodyMesh,   &quot;Body&quot;);
Entity.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Entity.SetSlotParent(&quot;Body&quot;, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

MeshComponent* Weapon = Entity.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(&quot;Weapon&quot;);
uint32_t SlotCount    = Entity.GetSlotCount&lt;MeshComponent&gt;();
Query Integration
Use ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; in entity queries to iterate all slots:
auto Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt;&gt;()
);

Library.ForEach(Query, [](ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        // Entry.Component — pointer to component
        // Entry.SlotID — unique identifier for this slot
    }
});
How Slots Work Internally
Slots are implemented as virtual TypeInfo entries. Each slot name is hashed into a unique TypeInfo that shares the memory layout of the base type but gets its own ID. From the archetype’s perspective, MeshComponent_Body, MeshComponent_Weapon, and MeshComponent_Armor are three entirely separate component types — each occupying its own column.
Unslotted vs Slotted Archetype Layout
Unslotted — an entity with TransformComponent and HealthComponent:
TypeRegistry
  &quot;TransformComponent&quot;  → ID: 0
  &quot;HealthComponent&quot;     → ID: 1

Archetype  Bitset: 1 1 0 0 0 ...
                   │ │
                   │ └─ HealthComponent (ID 1)
                   └─── TransformComponent (ID 0)

Columns (Structure of Arrays):
  Col[0]  TransformComponent  │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ E4 │ ...
  Col[1]  HealthComponent     │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ E4 │ ...

Slotted — an entity with TransformComponent and three MeshComponent slots:
TypeRegistry
  &quot;TransformComponent&quot;       → ID: 0
  &quot;MeshComponent&quot;            → ID: 1  ← base type, never set on any archetype
  &quot;MeshComponent_Body&quot;       → ID: 2  ← virtual (same struct, unique ID)
  &quot;MeshComponent_Weapon&quot;     → ID: 3  ← virtual
  &quot;MeshComponent_Armor&quot;      → ID: 4  ← virtual

SlotRegistry
  MeshComponent (ID 1)  →  [ Body (ID 2), Weapon (ID 3), Armor (ID 4) ]

Archetype  Bitset: 1 0 1 1 1 0 ...
                   │   │ │ │
                   │   │ │ └─ MeshComponent_Armor  (ID 4)
                   │   │ └─── MeshComponent_Weapon (ID 3)
                   │   └───── MeshComponent_Body   (ID 2)
                   └───────── TransformComponent   (ID 0)
                   NOTE: MeshComponent base (ID 1) is never set

Columns (Structure of Arrays):
  Col[0]  TransformComponent      │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...
  Col[1]  MeshComponent_Body      │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...  ← same sizeof(MeshComponent)
  Col[2]  MeshComponent_Weapon    │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...  ← same sizeof(MeshComponent)
  Col[3]  MeshComponent_Armor     │ E1 │ E2 │ E3 │ ...  ← same sizeof(MeshComponent)

The virtual TypeInfos are purely an ID trick — each slot column stores raw MeshComponent data. The SlotRegistry is the only thing that knows they all belong to the same base type, which is what ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; and query matching use to reassemble them.
Slot Names Drive Archetype Identity
Because each unique slot name produces a unique virtual TypeInfo ID, two entities with different slot name sets land in different archetypes, even if the slot count is identical:
// These three entities end up in THREE different archetypes:

Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(warrior, bodyMesh,  &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(warrior, swordMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);   // Arch A: [Body | Weapon]

Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(archer,  bodyMesh,  &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(archer,  bowMesh,   &quot;Bow&quot;);      // Arch B: [Body | Bow]

Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(mage,    bodyMesh,  &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(mage,    staffMesh, &quot;Staff&quot;);    // Arch C: [Body | Staff]
This splits entities across three separate archetypes, fragmenting memory and reducing ForEach iteration efficiency. Standardise slot names across entity types to keep related entities in the same archetype:
// ✅ All three share Arch A: [Body | Weapon] — one tight memory chunk
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(warrior, swordMesh,  &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(archer,  bowMesh,    &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(mage,    staffMesh,  &quot;Weapon&quot;);
Use a consistent vocabulary of slot names (e.g. &quot;Body&quot;, &quot;Weapon&quot;, &quot;Offhand&quot;) or a standardized namespace across all NPC types. Entities that genuinely differ in composition (a quadruped with four leg meshes vs. a biped) belong in separate archetypes anyway — that fragmentation is expected and correct.
Slot Hierarchies
Slots on a single entity can declare parent-child relationships using the slot hierarchy API. This is useful for expressing that a sword mesh belongs under a body mesh, or that a collider follows a specific mesh slot — without requiring any new component types or archetype changes.
Hierarchy data is stored in an invisible internal SlotHierarchyComponent that is automatically added to the entity on first use. You never interact with it directly.
Setting Up a Hierarchy
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, bodyMesh,   &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, swordMesh,  &quot;Sword&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;ColliderComponent&gt;(Entity, swordCollider, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;);

// Declare that &quot;Sword&quot; is a child of &quot;Body&quot;
Library.SetSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Body&quot;, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Declare that &quot;SwordCollider&quot; is a child of &quot;Sword&quot;
// Cross-type parenting is allowed — types don&#039;t need to match
Library.SetSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;);
Querying the Hierarchy
// Get the parent of &quot;Sword&quot; as a MeshComponent
MeshComponent* Parent = Library.GetParentComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Pointer overload — resolves the slot name from the pointer automatically
// Slightly more expensive due to the reverse column scan
MeshComponent* SwordPtr = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);
MeshComponent* ParentViaPtr = Library.GetParentComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, SwordPtr);

// Get all ColliderComponent slots that are children of &quot;Sword&quot;
ComponentSpan&lt;ColliderComponent&gt; Colliders = Library.GetChildrenComponents&lt;ColliderComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Pointer overload for children
MeshComponent* BodyPtr = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Body&quot;);
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; BodyChildren = Library.GetChildrenComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, BodyPtr);

// Get all slots of type T that have any parent (regardless of which parent)
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; AllParented = Library.GetChildrenComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Get all slots of type T that have no parent — the roots
ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Roots = Library.GetRootComponents&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
Removing a Relationship
// Remove the parent relationship from &quot;Sword&quot; — &quot;Sword&quot; becomes a root again
Library.ClearSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);

// Query if a slot has a parent
bool HasParent = Library.HasSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Sword&quot;);
Declaring Hierarchies on Prefabs
Slot hierarchies can be declared directly on an EntityPrefab so that every spawned entity already has the correct parent relationships — with no archetype migration cost at spawn time.
EntityPrefab WarriorPrefab;
WarriorPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(bodyMesh,    &quot;Body&quot;);
WarriorPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(swordMesh,   &quot;Sword&quot;);
WarriorPrefab.Add&lt;ColliderComponent&gt;(swordCol, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;);

// Declare hierarchy on the prefab template
WarriorPrefab.SetSlotParent(&quot;Body&quot; &quot;Sword&quot;);
WarriorPrefab.SetSlotParent(&quot;Sword&quot;, &quot;SwordCollider&quot;);

Library.BakePrefab(WarriorPrefab);

// Every spawned entity already has the hierarchy — no migration occurs
EntityHandle Warrior = Library.Instantiate(WarriorPrefab);
The prefab API mirrors the runtime API exactly:





















Prefab methodRuntime equivalentPrefab.SetSlotParent(&quot;Parent&quot;, &quot;Child&quot;)Library.SetSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Parent&quot;, &quot;Child&quot;)Prefab.ClearSlotParent(&quot;Child&quot;)Library.ClearSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Child&quot;)Prefab.HasSlotParent(&quot;Child&quot;)Library.HasSlotParent(Entity, &quot;Child&quot;)
Key Properties

Cross-type parenting is allowed. A ColliderComponent slot can be the child of a MeshComponent slot. The hierarchy stores slot names only — types are only used at the query level for the return value.
The SlotHierarchyComponent is invisible. It is never returned by general-purpose queries. Think of it as metadata attached to the entity, not a game-facing component.
No archetype change at runtime. Setting or clearing a parent relationship only modifies a std::unordered_map inside SlotHierarchyComponent. The entity does not migrate archetypes. When declared on a prefab, SlotHierarchyComponent is included in the baked archetype upfront, so spawn cost is zero.
Slots are unique per entity. Because slot names are unique across all component types on a single entity, no type disambiguation is needed in SetSlotParent or ClearSlotParent.

Entity: &quot;Warrior&quot;

  MeshComponent[&quot;Body&quot;]           ← root (no parent)
  ├── MeshComponent[&quot;Sword&quot;]      ← child of &quot;Body&quot;
  │   └── ColliderComponent[&quot;SwordCollider&quot;]  ← child of &quot;Sword&quot;
  └── MeshComponent[&quot;Shield&quot;]     ← child of &quot;Body&quot;
      └── ColliderComponent[&quot;ShieldCollider&quot;] ← child of &quot;Shield&quot;

Auto-Generated Slot Names
When a [[Slottable]] component is added without an explicit slot name, the engine automatically generates a name like &quot;ComponentType_0&quot;, &quot;ComponentType_1&quot;, etc. This provides a safety net for code that doesn’t explicitly track slot names.
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);      // Creates &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);     // Creates &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;

// Can still retrieve them
MeshComponent* First = Library.GetComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // Returns &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Best Practices: Always Use Explicit Slot Names
Do not rely on auto-generated slot names. While they provide a safety net, they make code brittle and hard to understand. Always assign meaningful, explicit names to slots:
// ✅ GOOD: Clear semantic names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
// Recommended to use namespaces for strings used frequently
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, MyNamespace::ArmorString);

// ❌ AVOID: Relying on auto-generated names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_2&quot;
Why explicit names matter:

Readability: Anyone reading GetComponent(entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;) immediately understands what’s being retrieved
Stability: If you refactor the order of additions, auto-generated indices shift; named slots never do
Debugging: Named slots appear in profilers and logs with semantic meaning
Intent: Your code explicitly states “this is the weapon mesh”, not “this is the second mesh”

Auto-generated names exist only as a fallback for simple prototypes or one-off code. Production code should always use explicit names.
Sparse Components
A sparse component carries data exactly like a regular component, but it is stored in a side table keyed by entity rather than in the entity’s archetype. Adding or removing one therefore never migrates the entity between archetypes — it is a hash-table insert/erase, not a structural change.
Declare one by inheriting CatalystSparseComponent:
struct [[Reflect]] StunnedComponent : Alchemy::CatalystSparseComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(StunnedComponent)

    float RemainingSeconds = 0.0f;
};
Usage
The API is identical to a regular component — the storage policy is the only difference, and it is resolved at compile time from the base struct:
Library.AddComponent&lt;StunnedComponent&gt;(Entity, { .RemainingSeconds = 2.0f });
StunnedComponent* Stun = Library.GetComponent&lt;StunnedComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;StunnedComponent&gt;(Entity);
Sparse components are also queryable transparently. A sparse component is bound into a ForEach lambda as a plain T&amp;, exactly like an archetype component — the query system filters entities by sparse presence and hands you the data:
auto Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent, StunnedComponent&gt;());

Library.ForEach(Query, [](TransformComponent&amp; Transform, StunnedComponent&amp; Stun)
{
    Stun.RemainingSeconds -= DeltaTime;  // mutates the sparse store in place
});
Slots, prefabs, and the EntityRef / EntityCommandBuffer / EntityTransaction surfaces all work with sparse components the same way they do with regular ones.
When to Use Sparse
Choose CatalystSparseComponent over CatalystComponent when:

The component is added and removed frequently — e.g. a transient StunnedComponent flipped many times a second. Each archetype-component add/remove is a structural migration; the sparse equivalent is not.
The component lives on only a small fraction of entities and you don’t want its mere presence to fragment otherwise-identical entities across extra archetypes.

The trade-off is iteration locality: archetype components are swept contiguously in SoA memory, whereas joining a sparse component into a query costs a side-table lookup per entity. For data that lives on most entities and is read every frame, keep it a regular CatalystComponent.
Sparse adds and removes raise the same Observer events as archetype components: AddElement / RemoveElement for changes to a live entity, CreateEntity when an entity is spawned from a prefab already holding one, and DestroyEntity when a holder is destroyed. An observer watches a sparse type exactly like any other element.
Toggle Components
Components can be disabled and re-enabled at runtime without destroying them. A disabled component’s data is fully preserved in memory — it is simply invisible to queries, so processors that iterate that component type skip the entity entirely with zero per-iteration overhead.
This is the correct tool for world streaming, LOD transitions, and any scenario where entities or components should temporarily stop participating in simulation without the cost of destruction and reconstruction.
How It Works
Disabling a component performs a single archetype migration. The entity moves from an archetype containing T into one containing an internal __Disabled__T virtual type. Because the query’s cached archetype list never includes that destination archetype, disabled entities are never discovered — there is no per-entity branch or check.
Before DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E):
  Archetype [Transform | MeshComponent]   ← query sees this

After:
  Archetype [Transform | __Disabled__MeshComponent]  ← query does NOT see this

Re-enabling performs the reverse migration and restores the original data exactly.
Basic API
// Disable — entity disappears from MeshComponent queries immediately
Library.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Enable — entity reappears, all data intact
Library.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Toggle — flips current state
Library.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Query state
bool bDisabled = Library.IsComponentDisabled&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);

// Read data while disabled, without re-enabling
MeshComponent* Data = Library.GetDisabledComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
DisableComponent is a no-op if the entity does not have the component or if it is already disabled.
Slot-Specific Overloads
When a component is slottable and an entity carries multiple slots, the no-argument DisableComponent&lt;T&gt; disables all slots of that type at once. To target a single slot, use the slot name or SlotID overloads:
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, bodyMesh,   &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Disable only the weapon — &quot;Body&quot; remains active and visible in queries
Library.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Enable it again
Library.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Toggle by name
Library.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Query state by name
bool bWeaponDisabled = Library.IsComponentDisabled&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Read disabled slot data
MeshComponent* WeaponData = Library.GetDisabledComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
When iterating a ComponentSpan and you already have a SlotID, use the ID overload to avoid re-hashing the name:
Library.ForEach(Query, [&amp;](EntityHandle E, ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        if (ShouldStreamOut(Entry.Component))
        {
            // Zero hashing cost — SlotID comes directly from the span entry
            Library.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E, Entry.SlotID);
        }
    }
});
Observer Events
Observers can listen for EnableComponent and DisableComponent events separately from AddElement / RemoveElement:
class OnMeshDisabledObserver : public IObserver
{
public:
    OnMeshDisabledObserver()
    {
        ObservedElement = TypeRegistry::GetType(MeshComponent::StaticName());
        ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::DisableComponent;
    }

    void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Context.AffectedEntities contains entities whose MeshComponent was just disabled
    }
};
ObserverOperation::Toggle is a convenience alias for EnableComponent | DisableComponent if you want to react to both:
ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::Toggle;
Performance
Because disabled entities live in a completely separate archetype, query iteration scales linearly with the number of active entities only. Disabling 50% of entities reduces ForEach time by approximately 50% — there is no scan, skip, or branch for disabled entities.
The migration cost on DisableComponent / EnableComponent is the same as a regular AddComponent / RemoveComponent archetype transition. This is a boundary event, not a per-frame cost.
Constructors
Catalyst supports Constructor Annotations. This allows you to run specific initialization logic whenever a component is added to an entity, which is useful for registering data with external systems or generating unique IDs.
These constructors are executed:

Immediately after AddComponent.
During EntityTransaction::Commit.
During EntityPrefab::Instantiate.

// Registering a constructor
AnnotationRegistry::Get().Bind&lt;MyComponent&gt;()
    .Add&lt;ConstructorAnnotation&gt;([](void* Ptr) {
        auto* Comp = static_cast&lt;MyComponent*&gt;(Ptr);
        Comp-&gt;UniqueID = GNextID++;
    });
Architectural Details (Advanced)
Memory Layout (SoA)
Components are stored in Archetypes using a Structure of Arrays (SoA) format. All components of the same type for a specific archetype are stored contiguously in memory.
Pointer Stability
Catalyst uses Chunked Memory (16KB Pages) for component storage. This ensures Pointer Stability: a pointer returned by GetComponent will remain valid for the lifetime of that component on that entity, even if millions of other entities are spawned or other archetypes reallocate.
Element Masks and Identification
An entity’s archetype composition is represented by an element mask — a growable bitset in which each bit corresponds to one archetype-resident type (a component or an archetype marker). Masks are compared with bitwise operations, which is what makes archetype query matching O(1) per archetype.
Bits are indexed by a compact element index that the ElementRegistry assigns lazily the first time a type is actually used as an archetype element — not by the type’s global reflection ID. Only types that participate in archetypes consume a bit, and the mask grows as needed, so there is no fixed ceiling on the number of component or marker types a project may define. Sparse components and sparse markers live entirely outside this mask (in their side tables) and so cost no element index at all.
See Also

Entity Query — querying entities by component composition
Entity Prefab — defining component defaults as reusable templates
Annotations — constructor annotations and other component metadata

Catalyst/Entity-Command-Buffer.content:
Entity Command Buffer
An EntityCommandBuffer (ECB) records structural changes — adding/removing components and markers, destroying entities, instantiating prefabs, toggling components — and applies them later in a single Playback() pass.
It exists because direct structural changes (AddComponent, RemoveComponent, DestroyEntity, …) are not safe to call while a query is iterating. Mutating an archetype mid-ForEach reallocates the very memory being walked, which is undefined behavior. The ECB lets you record the intent during iteration and apply it once iteration is complete.
EntityCommandBuffer Buffer;

Library.ForEach(DyingQuery, [&amp;Buffer](EntityHandle Entity, HealthComponent&amp; Health)
{
    if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
    {
        // Recorded, not executed — safe inside ForEach
        Buffer.AddMarker&lt;DeadMarker&gt;(Entity);
        Buffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
    }
});

// Apply everything now that iteration is finished
Buffer.Playback(Library);
Why It’s Safe From Worker Threads
Recording never touches the EntityLibrary and never mutates any registry. A command is just bytes appended to a page:

For typed commands, the TypeInfo* is resolved at record time (the type already exists) and stored as a pointer.
For slot names and virtual marker names, the name bytes are copied into the buffer and the slot/marker type is fabricated/interned at Playback time on the main thread. This is why those overloads take a std::string_view / StringView rather than a pre-resolved type — name interning is not thread-safe, but copying bytes is.

That means a buffer can be filled from a job-system worker without locking. The buffer itself is move-only and is not internally synchronized: use one buffer per recording thread, not one buffer shared across threads.
Recording Commands
Components
Buffer.AddComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity);                 // default-constructed
Buffer.AddComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity, Data);           // with initial data
Buffer.RemoveComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity);
Works for both archetype (CatalystComponent) and sparse (CatalystSparseComponent) policies — the storage is resolved from the base type at playback. The component is constructed directly in its target storage during Playback().
Slotted Components
Buffer.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);  // with data
Buffer.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);              // default-constructed slot
Buffer.RemoveComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);           // removes the single named slot
The slot name bytes are copied into the buffer; the slot’s virtual TypeInfo is resolved at playback. See Component Slots.
Markers
Buffer.AddMarker&lt;T&gt;(Entity);       // typed (CatalystMarker / CatalystSparseMarker)
Buffer.RemoveMarker&lt;T&gt;(Entity);
Virtual (string-named) markers are recorded by name. The name is copied into the buffer and the marker type is fabricated at playback:
Buffer.AddMarker(Entity, &quot;Burning&quot;);              // sparse by default (IsSparse = true)
Buffer.AddMarker(Entity, &quot;Burning&quot;, /*IsSparse=*/ false);  // archetype-resident
Buffer.RemoveMarker(Entity, &quot;Burning&quot;);
Toggling Components
Disable, enable, and toggle map to the same archetype-migration mechanism described in Toggle Components. The toggle direction for ToggleComponent is decided at playback, so it reflects the entity’s real state at apply time, not at record time.
Buffer.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);              // all slots of T
Buffer.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);    // one named slot
Buffer.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity, SlotID);      // one slot, no re-hash

Buffer.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);               // + name / SlotID overloads
Buffer.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);               // + name / SlotID overloads
The SlotID overloads are a no-op if that slot type was never registered (the component was never added).
Entities and Prefabs
Buffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
Buffer.Instantiate(&amp;BakedPrefab);   // prefab pointer must outlive Playback()
The prefab must already be baked (see Entity Prefab) and must remain alive until Playback() runs — only the pointer is stored.
Arbitrary Logic
For anything the typed commands don’t cover, enqueue a lambda. It runs during playback with the library passed in:
Buffer.Enqueue([](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib)
{
    // Arbitrary deferred work
});
Applying and Resetting
Buffer.Playback(Library);   // applies all recorded commands in record order
Buffer.Clear();             // resets the buffer for reuse without freeing pages
Commands are replayed in the order they were recorded. Playback() does not implicitly clear the buffer — call Clear() to reuse it (which keeps the allocated pages, so the next frame’s recording is allocation-free).
Use Inside Processors
Inside a processor’s Execute, a per-frame command buffer is provided on the ProcessorContext as Context.Commands (also reachable via Context.GetCommandBuffer()). Always record structural changes there rather than mutating the library directly — the library flushes it automatically after all processors’ Execute methods return.
void DeathProcessor::Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context)
{
    Context.Library.ForEach(DyingQuery, [&amp;Context](EntityHandle Entity, HealthComponent&amp; Health)
    {
        if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
            Context.Commands.DestroyEntity(Entity);
    });
    // No manual Playback — the library flushes Context.Commands after the tick
}



                  NOTE



Signals are a separate, also-thread-safe path that does not require an ECB — signal raising uses its own lock-free queue. Reach for the ECB for structural changes; reach for signals for events.


How It Works (Advanced)
Recording uses a page-based linear allocator: 16 KB CommandPages holding a tight little instruction stream of [opcode][args...]. Appending a command is O(1) — bump a pointer, memcpy the arguments. When a page fills, the next is reused (after Clear()) or a new one is allocated. For typical single-frame usage the buffer reaches a steady-state page count and stops allocating entirely.
Playback() walks the pages linearly, which is cache-friendly, decodes each opcode, and dispatches to the library’s internal structural-change entry points. Enqueue’d lambdas are stored in a side array and referenced by index from the instruction stream so they replay in the correct interleaved order.

The C++ header EntityCommandBuffer.h is the source of truth for the exact set of overloads.

See Also

Entity Library — direct (immediate) structural changes and the transaction batching alternative
Toggle Components — the disable/enable/toggle mechanism the ECB defers
Tags and Markers — typed and virtual markers
Processor — ProcessorContext::Commands and automatic flushing
Signal Processor — the lock-free event path that does not need an ECB

Catalyst/Entity-Library.content:
Entity Library
An EntityLibrary is the top-level container for an entire ECP world. Every entity, component, archetype, query, processor, observer, and relation lives inside one. There is no global world — you always work through a library instance.
Multiple libraries can coexist simultaneously, each representing an entirely independent ECP world. A running game might have one library for the game world, one for the editor viewport, and another inside the asset manager.
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    EntityLibrary                    │
│                                                     │
│  Entities &amp; Records      Archetypes                 │
│  ┌────────────────┐      ┌──────────────────────┐   │
│  │ Index → Record │      │ [TransformComponent, │   │
│  │   0  → null    │      │  HealthComponent]    │   │
│  │   1  → Arch A  │      │   Row 0: Entity 1    │   │
│  │   2  → Arch B  │      │   Row 1: Entity 3    │   │
│  │   3  → Arch A  │      └──────────────────────┘   │
│  └────────────────┘      ┌──────────────────────┐   │
│                          │  [TransformComponent,│   │
│  Processors              │   VelocityComponent] │   │
│  ┌────────────────┐      │    Row 0: Entity 2   │   │
│  │ MovementProc   │      └──────────────────────┘   │
│  │ RenderProc     │                                 │
│  │ AIProc         │      Registered Queries         │
│  └────────────────┘      ┌──────────────────────┐   │
│                          │  Q0: All&lt;Transform&gt;  │   │
│                          │  Q1: All&lt;Transform,  │   │
│                          │      Velocity&gt;       │   │
│                          └──────────────────────┘   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Creating a Library
Declare an EntityLibrary anywhere. Libraries are value types with value semantics — they can be owned by subsystems, editor tabs, game modules, or tests.
EntityLibrary Library;

// Optional: assign an owning world (for world-level libraries)
Library.OwningWorld = &amp;MyWorld;
Library Tags
Library tags are used to control which processors attach to which libraries. When a library is registered with the EntityLibrarySubsystem, it automatically receives all processors whose LibraryFilter tag query matches the library’s tags.
// Mark this library as a game world library
Library.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_GameWorld);

// Mark as an editor viewport library
ViewportLibrary.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_Editor_EditorViewport);
A processor declared with LibraryFilter.RequireTag(Engine_GameWorld) will only attach to libraries tagged with Engine_GameWorld — not to the editor viewport library. This is the primary mechanism for controlling processor scope.
Registering with the Engine
To have the engine tick your library every frame and auto-attach processors, register it with the EntityLibrarySubsystem.
EntityLibrarySubsystem* Subsystem = Engine.GetSubsystem&lt;EntityLibrarySubsystem&gt;();

// Register — all matching processors are instantiated immediately
Subsystem-&gt;Register(&amp;Library);

// Unregister when the library is no longer active
Subsystem-&gt;Unregister(&amp;Library);
Scoped Registration (RAII)
For temporary libraries (editor tabs, test contexts, etc.), use RegisterScoped to guarantee automatic unregistration when the owning scope exits.
{
    ScopedLibraryRegistration Scope = Subsystem-&gt;RegisterScoped(&amp;ViewportLibrary);
    // ViewportLibrary is now ticked every frame

} // ← Unregistered here automatically
Creating Entities
Basic Entity Creation
// Create an entity with no components
EntityHandle Entity = Library.CreateEntity();

// Immediately check if a handle is valid
if(Entity.IsValid())
{
    Library.AddComponent&lt;TransformComponent&gt;(Entity);
}

// Check if an entity is still alive (not destroyed)
bool bAlive = Library.IsEntityAlive(Entity);
EntityRef — the short-form, library-bound API
CreateEntity() actually returns an EntityRef: a lightweight proxy that pairs the entity
handle with its owning library. This lets you call per-entity operations directly on the entity
instead of routing every call back through the library:
// The verbose, library-first form still works:
Library.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity, { .CurrentHealth = 50.0f });
HealthComponent* Health = Library.GetComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);

// The short form, via an EntityRef:
EntityRef Entity = Library.CreateEntity();
Entity.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;({ .CurrentHealth = 50.0f });
HealthComponent* Health = Entity.GetComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;();
Entity.RemoveComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;();
An EntityRef mirrors the entire per-entity surface of EntityLibrary (components, slots, slot
hierarchy, markers, toggles, and relations) as one-to-one forwards.
It is foolproof. A bare EntityHandle is just a 64-bit id, so passing it into the wrong
library silently resolves to whatever entity happens to share that index/generation. An EntityRef
carries its library, so it always resolves against the correct library.
It interops freely with handles. EntityRef converts implicitly to EntityHandle, so it drops
into any handle-based call, and EntityHandle Handle = Library.CreateEntity(); keeps compiling:
EntityRef Ref = Library.CreateEntity();
EntityHandle Handle = Ref;                       // implicit conversion
Library.GetComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Ref);      // usable anywhere a handle is expected
Wrap an existing handle in a ref with Library.Ref(Handle):
EntityHandle Handle = GetSomeHandle();
EntityRef Entity = Library.Ref(Handle);
Entity.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;();
Queries can hand you an EntityRef directly — just declare the lambda parameter as EntityRef
(by value) instead of EntityHandle:
Library.ForEach(Query, [](EntityRef Entity, HealthComponent&amp; Health)
{
    if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
        Entity.AddMarker&lt;DeadMarker&gt;();
});
Take the EntityRef by value (not by reference) — it is a per-row temporary, the same way the
existing EntityHandle parameter is.

EntityRef holds a raw, non-owning pointer to its library. The contract is the same as for a bare
handle: a ref must not outlive the library it came from.

Performance
EntityRef is zero-cost in optimized builds. Binding an EntityRef query parameter instead of an
EntityHandle measured +1.85% in release builds — within run-to-run noise — because the proxy is
just a pointer plus a handle and the per-entity construction inlines away entirely. The handle column is
bound exactly as before; the ref is materialized on the stack per row and never stored.



                  Debug builds 



In an unoptimized Debug build the same micro-benchmark shows a large gap (the proxy’s constructor and
by-value return are not inlined, so a ~2.5 ns loop body balloons to ~100 ns). This is purely a
non-inlining artifact and disappears under optimization. The only place to prefer a bare EntityHandle
parameter is if you are profiling a hot query loop in a Debug build specifically.


Destroying Entities
Library.DestroyEntity(Entity);

// The handle is now stale — IsEntityAlive returns false
// IsEntityAlive uses the generation counter, so stale handles
// are detected even if the entity index has been reused
Entity Handle Internals
EntityHandle (64-bit)
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Upper 32 bits: Generation │  Lower 32 bits: Index │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Generation: incremented each time an index is recycled
  Index 0:    permanently reserved as ENTITY_NULL

// Validity check — generation mismatch means the slot was reused
bool bAlive = (Library.Generations[Handle.GetIndex()] == Handle.GetGeneration());

The Entity Lifecycle
A typical entity goes through the following stages:
1. CreateEntity()        → Allocate an index, bump generation, no archetype
        │
        ▼
2. AddComponent&lt;T&gt;()     → Place entity into a matching archetype
   AddComponent&lt;T&gt;()     → Migrate to a new archetype (edges are cached)
        │
        ▼
3. IsEntityAlive()       → true (generation matches)
   GetComponent&lt;T&gt;()     → returns pointer into archetype column
   ForEach(...)          → entity is visited by matching queries
        │
        ▼
4. RemoveComponent&lt;T&gt;()  → Migrate to a smaller archetype
        │
        ▼
5. DestroyEntity()       → Entity removed from archetype
                           Index placed in FreeIndices pool
                           Generation incremented (stale handles detected)

Structural Changes
AddComponent and RemoveComponent
Every AddComponent or RemoveComponent moves the entity to a different archetype. These archetype migrations are cheap because the library maintains a cached edge graph: moving from archetype A to “A + T” re-uses a pre-calculated pointer.
// Adding a component (migrates to a larger archetype)
TransformComponent&amp; Transform = Library.AddComponent&lt;TransformComponent&gt;(Entity);
Transform.Position = {0.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f};

// Removing a component (migrates to a smaller archetype)
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;VelocityComponent&gt;(Entity);
Entity Transaction (Batched Changes)
If you need to add or remove several components at once, use an EntityTransaction. It batches all changes into a single archetype migration rather than one per add/remove, which is significantly cheaper for large sets of changes.
// Without a transaction — three migrations:
Library.AddComponent&lt;RenderComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.AddComponent&lt;ShadowComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.RemoveComponent&lt;PlaceholderTag&gt;(Entity);

// With a transaction — one migration:
auto Transaction = Library.Modify(Entity);
Transaction.Add&lt;RenderComponent&gt;();
Transaction.Add&lt;ShadowComponent&gt;();
Transaction.Remove&lt;PlaceholderTag&gt;();
Transaction.Commit(); // ← single archetype migration happens here
// Note: components are NOT visible on the entity until Commit()
The transaction is especially valuable during world loading or prefab post-processing when an entity receives many components in sequence.
Deferred Changes (EntityCommandBuffer)
Direct structural changes (AddComponent, DestroyEntity, etc.) are not safe to call inside a ForEach callback — modifying archetypes while iterating over them is undefined behavior. The EntityCommandBuffer lets you record commands during iteration and apply them afterward.
EntityCommandBuffer Buffer;

Library.ForEach(DyingQuery, [&amp;Buffer](HealthComponent&amp; Health, EntityHandle Entity)
{
    if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
    {
        // Safe — this records the command, doesn&#039;t execute it yet
        Buffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
        Buffer.AddComponent&lt;DeadMarker&gt;(Entity);
    }
});

// Apply all recorded commands now that iteration is complete
Buffer.Playback(Library); // also calls Clear() automatically
Supported Commands
Buffer.AddComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity, Data);           // also slotted: (Entity, Data, &quot;Slot&quot;)
Buffer.RemoveComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity);              // also slotted: (Entity, &quot;Slot&quot;)
Buffer.AddMarker&lt;T&gt;(Entity);                    // also virtual: (Entity, &quot;Name&quot;, IsSparse)
Buffer.RemoveMarker&lt;T&gt;(Entity);
Buffer.DisableComponent&lt;T&gt;(Entity);             // + EnableComponent / ToggleComponent
Buffer.DestroyEntity(Entity);
Buffer.Instantiate(&amp;BakedPrefab);  // prefab must outlive Playback()
Buffer.Enqueue([](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) { /* arbitrary logic */ });
The buffer uses a page-based allocator (16 KB pages) and is designed to be zero-allocation for typical usage within a single frame. Recording is thread-safe per buffer — slot/marker names are copied in and resolved at playback — so a buffer can be filled from job-system workers.
See Entity Command Buffer for the complete API, including slotted, virtual-marker, and toggle overloads, and the threading contract.
Processors and Command Buffers
Inside a processor’s Execute method, a command buffer is available via ProcessorContext. Always use it for structural changes rather than modifying the library directly:
void MyProcessor::Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context)
{
    Context.Library.ForEach(MyQuery, [&amp;Context](HealthComponent&amp; Health, EntityHandle Entity)
    {
        if(Health.CurrentHealth &lt;= 0.0f)
        {
            Context.Commands.DestroyEntity(Entity);
        }
    });
    // The library flushes Context.Commands automatically after all processor Execute&#039;s return
}
Ticking and Lifecycle
Manual Tick
When you own a library outside the subsystem, call Update yourself:
Library.Update(DeltaTime);
Update runs all processors registered on the library and flushes all pending observer events.

Note: Do not call Update inside Crucible tests. Tests should call processor or query methods directly.

Clearing a Library
Clear() resets the entire library - all entities, archetypes, queries, and processor state are destroyed.
Library.Clear();
Multiple Concurrent Libraries
The real power of the library model is that several independent ECP worlds can run simultaneously. Each has its own entities, archetypes, and processors, and they never interfere with each other.
                        ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
                        │        EntityLibrarySubsystem       │
                        │                                     │
                        │  ┌────────────┐  ┌────────────────┐ │
                        │  │  GameWorld │  │ EditorViewport │ │
                        │  │  Library   │  │   Library      │ │
                        │  │            │  │                │ │
                        │  │ Processor  │  │ Processor      │ │
                        │  │ (Game tag) │  │ (Editor tag)   │ │
                        │  └────────────┘  └────────────────┘ │
                        │                                     │
                        │  ┌─────────────────────────────┐    │
                        │  │   AssetManager Library      │    │
                        │  │   (Asset Manager tag)       │    │
                        │  └─────────────────────────────┘    │
                        └─────────────────────────────────────┘
Each library is only ticked and modified by processors whose LibraryFilter matches its tags. An editor viewport library and a game world library can coexist with zero crosstalk.
Merging Libraries
Merge bulk-copies all entities and components from one library into another. The source library is left unmodified.
// Copy everything from ChunkLibrary into the main world
MainLibrary.Merge(ChunkLibrary);

// Preserve original EntityHandles from the source (default)
MainLibrary.Merge(ChunkLibrary, /*bPreserveIDs=*/ true);

// Assign new handles to avoid ID collisions across independently-loaded worlds
MainLibrary.Merge(ChunkLibrary, /*bPreserveIDs=*/ false);
The merge is archetype-aware — for each archetype in the source, it calls GetOrCreateArchetype in the target, bulk-allocates rows, then copies all component columns via CopyConstructor (or memcpy as a fallback).
Merging is useful for:

Streaming open world chunks into a single runtime library
Consolidating distributed ECS registries
Copying test fixture state between test runs

Serialization
EntityLibrarySerializer provides binary save and load for an entire library.
#include &quot;Catalyst/Serialization/EntityLibrarySerializer.h&quot;

// Save
EntityLibrarySerializer::Serialize(Library, &quot;SavedWorld.bin&quot;);

// Load
EntityLibrarySerializer::Deserialize(Library, &quot;SavedWorld.bin&quot;);
The binary format uses the ALCH magic number and a version field. On load:

Archetypes are recreated via GetOrCreateArchetype.
Entity rows are bulk-allocated.
Component data is reconstructed via each type’s registered serializer.


Note: Components without a registered serializer are skipped during load with a warning. Ensure all persistent component types have serialization support via the reflection system’s operator&amp;(Archive&amp;).

Processor Management
Processors can be added to a library either automatically (via EntityLibrarySubsystem and LibraryFilter) or manually.
// Manual attachment — for specialized or test processors
Library.AddProcessor(new MyProcessor());

// Inline processor — lambda-based, no class needed
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;MovementProcessor&quot;)
        .OnExecute([](ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx) {
            Ctx.Library.ForEach(MoveQuery, [](TransformComponent&amp; T, VelocityComponent&amp; V) {
                T.Position += V.Velocity * Ctx.DeltaTime;
            });
        })
	);

// Remove a specific processor
Library.RemoveProcessor(ProcessorPtr);
For production code, prefer class-based processors registered via AutoRegisterProcessor&lt;T&gt; so they attach automatically to all matching libraries.
Common Patterns
Game World Setup
// In a world subsystem or game module:
EntityLibrary GameLibrary;
GameLibrary.OwningWorld = &amp;World;
GameLibrary.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_GameWorld);

ScopedLibraryRegistration Scope = Subsystem-&gt;RegisterScoped(&amp;GameLibrary);
// All processors tagged Engine_GameWorld are now active
Editor Viewport
EntityLibrary ViewportLibrary;
ViewportLibrary.LibraryTags.AddTag(Engine_Editor_EditorViewport);

// Create the camera entity directly — no prefab needed for one-offs
EntityHandle Camera = ViewportLibrary.CreateEntity();
ViewportLibrary.AddComponent&lt;TransformComponent&gt;(Camera);
ViewportLibrary.AddComponent&lt;CameraComponent&gt;(Camera);

ScopedLibraryRegistration Scope = Subsystem-&gt;RegisterScoped(&amp;ViewportLibrary);
// Tab close → Scope destructor unregisters automatically
Standalone Library (No Subsystem)
Useful for asset processing, tools, or simulation previews that should not participate in the main game tick:
EntityLibrary AssetLibrary;
// No tags — no processors auto-attach
// No registration — not ticked by the subsystem

// Manually tick if needed
AssetLibrary.Update(DeltaTime);
// Or query directly without ticking
AssetLibrary.ForEach(Query, [](MyComponent&amp; C) { ... });
Crucible Tests
#if ALCHEMY_WITH_CRUCIBLE
BEGIN_SPEC(LibrarySpec, &quot;Catalyst.EntityLibrary&quot;)
END_SPEC(LibrarySpec)

void LibrarySpec::Define()
{
    Describe(&quot;Entity lifecycle&quot;, [this]()
    {
        It(&quot;should invalidate a handle after destruction&quot;, [this]()
        {
            EntityLibrary Library;
            EntityHandle Entity = Library.CreateEntity();
            Library.AddComponent&lt;HealthComponent&gt;(Entity);

            TestTrue(&quot;alive before destroy&quot;, Library.IsEntityAlive(Entity));
            Library.DestroyEntity(Entity);
            TestFalse(&quot;dead after destroy&quot;, Library.IsEntityAlive(Entity));
        });
    });
}
#endif
See Also

Components — adding, removing, and querying components and slots
Entity Prefab — high-performance entity spawning via baked blueprints
Entity Query — ForEach, ForEachParallel, and filtered iteration
Entity Command Buffer — deferring structural changes recorded during iteration
Processor — processors that run against a library every tick
Relations — typed directional links between entities within a library
Tags and Markers — lightweight per-entity flags

Catalyst/Entity-Prefab.content:
Entity Prefab
An EntityPrefab is a high-performance blueprint for creating entities. It allows you to define a composition of components and their default values once, then spawn thousands of identical entities with virtually zero overhead.
Creating a Prefab
Prefabs act as mutable containers during configuration. You can add components and immediately modify their data.
EntityPrefab OrcPrefab;

// Add components and tweak values
auto&amp; Stats = OrcPrefab.Add&lt;StatsComponent&gt;();
Stats.Health = 500;
Stats.Strength = 20;

OrcPrefab.Add&lt;AIComponent&gt;({ .Behavior = EAIBehavior::Aggressive });
OrcPrefab.Add&lt;TransformComponent&gt;();
Adding Component Slots
Prefabs support the same slotted component API as the EntityLibrary. Use the two-parameter overload to add multiple instances:
EntityPrefab NPCPrefab;

// Add unslotted base component
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(defaultMesh);

// Add slotted components with names
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(bodyMesh, &quot;Body&quot;);
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(weaponMesh, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(armorMesh, &quot;Armor&quot;);

// Retrieve and modify slots before baking
MeshComponent* Weapon = NPCPrefab.Get&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(&quot;Weapon&quot;);
if (Weapon) {
    Weapon-&gt;Visibility = true;
}
The slot data is preserved and applied to every entity instantiated from the prefab, just like regular components.
Sparse Components
Prefabs support sparse components as well. Add them exactly like any other component. Because they live outside the archetype, they are not baked into the target archetype — instead the prefab’s template data is written into each spawned entity’s side table at instantiation, so they add no archetype-migration cost to the spawn.
OrcPrefab.Add&lt;StunnedComponent&gt;({ .RemainingSeconds = 5.0f });
Best Practices: Always Use Explicit Slot Names
When working with slotted components in prefabs, always assign meaningful, explicit names to your slots. Do not rely on auto-generated slot names. While the engine supports auto-generation as a safety net (e.g., &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;, &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;), it should only be used in simple prototypes or one-off code.
// ✅ GOOD: Clear semantic names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Body&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, &quot;Weapon&quot;);
// Recommended to use namespaces for strings used frequently
NPCPrefab.Add&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity, MyNamespace::ArmorString);

// ❌ AVOID: Relying on auto-generated names
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_0&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_1&quot;
Library.AddComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(entity);  // &quot;MeshComponent_2&quot;
Why explicit names matter:

Readability: Anyone reading Get&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(&quot;Weapon&quot;) immediately understands what’s being retrieved
Stability: If you refactor the order of additions, auto-generated indices shift; named slots never do
Debugging: Named slots appear in profilers and logs with semantic meaning
Intent: Your code explicitly states “this is the weapon mesh”, not “this is the second mesh”

Auto-generated names exist only as a fallback for simple prototypes or one-off code. Production prefabs should always use explicit names.
The Baking Process
Before a prefab can be spawned, it must be Baked. Baking is a one-time optimization step where the EntityLibrary pre-calculates the target archetype and organizes the component data into the engine’s internal memory layout.
// This resolves the Archetype and caches memory offsets once.
Library.BakePrefab(OrcPrefab);
Instantiation (Spawning)
Once baked, you can instantiate entities from the prefab. This is the fastest way to create entities in Catalyst.
Single Spawn
Creates a single entity and returns its handle.
EntityHandle NewOrc = Library.Instantiate(OrcPrefab);
Bulk Spawn
The most optimized path for spawning many entities at once (e.g., world loading or unit waves).
// Spawns 1,000 entities in a single pass
Library.Instantiate(OrcPrefab, 1000);
Constructors
Prefabs fully support Constructor Annotations. When an entity is instantiated from a prefab:

The prefab’s tweaked data is copied into the entity.
The component’s Alchemical Constructor is executed.

This allows you to define “static” defaults in the prefab while still allowing every spawned entity to have unique logic (like a UniqueID or a SpawnTimestamp) generated at the moment of birth.
Performance Details (Advanced)
O(1) Spawning
Unlike the standard CreateEntity + AddComponent flow, Instantiate is an O(1) operation.

No Bitset Hashing: The target archetype is already known.
No Map Lookups: Column indices and Constructor pointers are pre-cached during the Bake step.
Raw Memcpy: Data is moved from the prefab to the archetype using highly optimized bulk memory copies.

Bulk Optimization
When using the bulk Instantiate overload, the engine performs a single memory allocation for the entire batch. This eliminates the “Resizing Wall” and ensures that spawning 100,000 entities is nearly as fast as spawning one, amortized across the batch.
See Also

Components — component slots and slot hierarchies, which prefabs support
Annotations — constructor annotations that run on prefab instantiation

Catalyst/Entity-Query.content:
Entity Query
The Entity Query system is the primary mechanism for retrieving entities and their components from an EntityLibrary. It is designed for maximum performance through Archetype Caching, ensuring that the cost of fetching data is proportional to the number of matching archetypes, not the total number of entities.
Defining a Query
Queries are built with BuildQuery&lt;...&gt;. The required components are spelled as template arguments, with const driving read/write access; optional filters chain off the result. The builder converts implicitly to an EntityQueryDescription.
// 1. Describe the requirements
EntityQueryID MoveQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;PositionComponent,        // required, read+write
               const VelocityComponent&gt;  // required, read-only (const)
		       .Without&lt;StaticTag&gt;());   // excluded

// (RegisterQuery returns a persistent EntityQueryID)
How const maps to access
The required-type list is what the Processor dependency solver reads to decide which processors may run in parallel. const is how you declare read-only:

































DeclarationMeaningTrequired, read + writeconst Trequired, read-only (parallel readers allowed)ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; / ComponentSpan&lt;const T&gt;required span, read+write / read-onlyInheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; / const InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt;required, matches any derived type of Base, read+write / read-onlyComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt;&gt; / ComponentSpan&lt;const InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt;&gt;required span of every derived type of Base present, read+write / read-onlya marker type (CatalystMarker / CatalystSparseMarker)required presence; const irrelevant (markers carry no data)



                  IMPORTANT



The const in the query and the const on the lambda parameter are two separate declarations: the query drives the solver, the lambda governs the compiler. If a lambda binds a component by mutable reference while the query declared it const, the solver may schedule a concurrent reader against you — a silent data race. Debug builds catch this mismatch with an assert in ForEach (compiled out of release). Keep them in agreement: read-only in the query ⇒ const T&amp; in the lambda.


Filters: Without, Optional, Bindless, Any, Tags

Without&lt;Ts...&gt;() — excludes entities carrying any of the listed components or markers (archetype-resident or sparse).
Optional&lt;Ts...&gt;() — the entity may or may not have these; they do not constrain matching. Bind them in the lambda with a pointer (T* / const T*), which is nullptr when absent. Archetype data components only. const drives read/write as usual.
Bindless&lt;Ts...&gt;() — required and present, but invisible to the dependency solver (you accept the data may be a frame stale). Always read-only.
Any&lt;Ts...&gt;() — the entity must have at least one of these (an OR filter). Filter-only: Any components are not bound into the lambda — read concrete data through a required component.
Tags(TagQuery) — filters by a hierarchical tag predicate evaluated per-entity against the entity’s TagComponent. See Filtering by Tags below.

Matching Rules

Required (BuildQuery&lt;...&gt; args): the entity must have every listed component/marker.
Any: the entity must have at least one component from the Any set.
Without: the entity must not have any listed component/marker.
Optional: does not affect matching; only changes how the component is bound (pointer-or-null).
Tags: the entity must carry a TagComponent whose tags satisfy every Tags() predicate (multiple Tags() calls are ANDed).
InheritsFrom: the entity must carry at least one component that derives from Base — see [[#inheritance-queries-inheritsfromt|Inheritance Queries (InheritsFrom&lt;T&gt;)]] below.

Wildcard Queries
A wildcard query tells Catalyst that the processor may read or write any component on the matching entities — not just the components explicitly listed in BuildQuery&lt;&gt;. This causes Catalyst to lock the entire matching archetype for the duration of the query.
Use .IsWildcard() to mark a query as a wildcard:
EntityQueryID StateMachineQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;StateMachineComponent&gt;()
        .IsWildcard());



                  WARNING



Wildcard queries are a blunt instrument. Because they force the dependency solver to treat the processor as a writer of every non-ignored component, they serialize against almost every other processor that touches those components. This can destroy parallelism. Only use a wildcard query when the set of components the processor may touch is truly unknown ahead of time — for example, a state machine or behavior tree that can add, remove, or modify arbitrary components based on runtime state.


In the example above, the query still only matches entities that have StateMachineComponent, but once it runs, no other write-query can process the same archetype chunk concurrently, and any processor reading or writing a non-ignored component will be ordered around this one.
The IgnoreWildcard Attribute
You can reduce the over-locking caused by wildcard queries by marking commonly-used, high-contention components with [[Reflect, IgnoreWildcard]]:
struct [[Reflect, IgnoreWildcard]] TransformComponent : Alchemy::CatalystComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(TransformComponent)
    // ...
};
Components marked IgnoreWildcard are excluded from wildcard archetype locks. If a wildcard processor actually needs to read or write an IgnoreWildcard component, it must declare that component explicitly in its query, like any normal query.
This is useful for components such as TransformComponent that are requested by many queries: without IgnoreWildcard, one wildcard query would serialize against every transform-reading processor in the library. With IgnoreWildcard, those processors can continue to run independently unless the wildcard processor explicitly opts into transform access.



                  IMPORTANT



IgnoreWildcard is not a free pass. It is a promise that this component is safe to access concurrently with wildcard processors unless explicitly declared. Only apply it to components whose data is not mutated by wildcard-driven systems, or whose access is already coordinated through other means.


Executing a Query
The most efficient way to process entities is using the ForEach and ForEachParallel methods.
Sequential Iteration (ForEach)
Used for standard logic that runs on a single thread. It resolves component pointers once per memory chunk to eliminate lookup overhead.
Library.ForEach(MoveQuery, [](PositionComponent&amp; Pos, const VelocityComponent&amp; Vel)
{
    Pos.Value += Vel.Value * DeltaTime;
});
Parallel Iteration (ForEachParallel)
Used for high-volume data processing. It automatically distributes entities across all available CPU cores using the engine’s Job System.
// Automatically uses the active JobBuilder context
Library.ForEachParallel(MoveQuery, [](PositionComponent&amp; Pos, const VelocityComponent&amp; Vel)
{
    // Logic runs in parallel across worker threads
    Pos.Value += Vel.Value * DeltaTime;
});
Queryless ForEach
For quick-and-dirty call sites — editor tools, [[Sigil]] UI code — where registering a query up front is overkill, ForEach, ForEachParallel, ForEachFiltered, and ForEachParallelFiltered all have an overload that skips the EntityQueryID entirely and derives the query from the lambda’s own parameters:
Library.ForEach([&amp;](TransformComponent&amp; Transform, const CameraComponent&amp;, InputStateComponent* Input)
{
    // TransformComponent/CameraComponent required (const drives read/write same as BuildQuery&lt;&gt;);
    // InputStateComponent* is Optional (pointer parameter, nullable); EntityHandle/EntityRef still
    // bind as identity params without needing to be named in the derived requirement set.
});
The description is derived once per distinct lambda (closure type) and cached on the library, so repeated calls (e.g. every frame from a widget) don’t re-pay the registration cost. This is a scoped-down convenience, not a replacement for processor-level queries: it does not communicate anything to the Processor dependency solver, so avoid it inside a processor’s Execute unless you warm the cache ahead of time (e.g. in Initialize) — registering a brand-new ad-hoc query while other processors may be reading Queries concurrently is a debug-time assert.
Span Queries (Multi-Instance Components)
When querying entities with slotted components (multiple instances of the same component type), use ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; in the query builder. This iterates all slots of that type on matching entities.
// Query for all entities with MeshComponent slots
EntityQueryID MeshQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt;&gt;()
);

// Iterate all entities and their mesh slots
Library.ForEach(MeshQuery, [](ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        // Entry.Component — pointer to the mesh
        // Entry.SlotID — identifier for this slot
        RenderMesh(Entry.Component);
    }
});
Mixed Span and Regular Components
You can combine span and regular components in the same query:
EntityQueryID Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent,            // Regular: single instance
               ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt;&gt;() // Span: multiple instances
);

Library.ForEach(Query, [](TransformComponent&amp; Transform, ComponentSpan&lt;MeshComponent&gt; Meshes)
{
    for (const auto&amp; Entry : Meshes)
    {
        RenderMeshAt(Entry.Component, Transform.Position);
    }
});
Span Query Semantics

BuildQuery&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt;&gt;(): Entity must have at least one slot of type T.
.Any&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt;&gt;(): entity may have slots of type T (OR filter).
.Without&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt;&gt;(): Entity must have zero slots of type T.

Span queries iterate only entities that have slots. Entities with only the unslotted base component do not match.
Inheritance Queries (InheritsFrom&lt;T&gt;)
Some component families are naturally polymorphic in shape even when the gameplay code treats them uniformly — a dozen debuff types that all get ticked and cleared the same way, for example. InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; matches any entity carrying a component that derives from Base, without you having to list every derived type by hand and without going stale if a new derived type is added later (including one introduced by a hot-loaded plugin).
There are two forms, mirroring the two ComponentSpan&lt;T&gt; shapes above:
struct DebuffComponent : Alchemy::CatalystComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(DebuffComponent)
    int SourceEntityID = 0;
};

struct PoisonDebuff : DebuffComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(PoisonDebuff)
    int DamagePerTick = 0;
};

struct SilenceDebuff : DebuffComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(SilenceDebuff)
    float RemainingDuration = 0;
};

// Single form — binds ONE Base* per matching entity.
auto DebuffQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(BuildQuery&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt;&gt;());

Library.ForEach(DebuffQuery, [](InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt; Debuff)
{
    Debuff-&gt;SourceEntityID; // any field declared on DebuffComponent itself
});

// Span form — binds EVERY derived type present on the entity.
auto DebuffSpanQuery = Library.RegisterQuery(BuildQuery&lt;ComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt;&gt;&gt;());

Library.ForEach(DebuffSpanQuery, [](ComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt;&gt; Debuffs)
{
    for(auto&amp; Entry : Debuffs)
    {
        Entry.Component-&gt;SourceEntityID; // any field declared on DebuffComponent itself
    }
});
Downcasting to the Concrete Type
Both forms let you recover the concrete derived type with .As&lt;Derived&gt;() — it returns the downcast pointer, or nullptr if the bound component isn’t actually a Derived, mirroring a dynamic_cast check-and-use pattern. Unlike dynamic_cast, it works whether or not Base is polymorphic, because the check is driven by TypeRegistry metadata (the concrete type resolved once per chunk by the query, not RTTI), not a vtable:
// Single form:
Library.ForEach(DebuffQuery, [](InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt; Debuff)
{
    if(PoisonDebuff* Poison = Debuff.As&lt;PoisonDebuff&gt;())
    {
        Poison-&gt;DamagePerTick;
    }
});

// Span form — same method on each Entry:
Library.ForEach(DebuffSpanQuery, [](ComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt;&gt; Debuffs)
{
    for(auto&amp; Entry : Debuffs)
    {
        if(SilenceDebuff* Silence = Entry.As&lt;SilenceDebuff&gt;())
        {
            Silence-&gt;RemainingDuration;
        }
    }
});
Choosing Single vs Span

Use InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; when each entity carries at most one derived type of Base at a time — the common case for something like a unit’s single active debuff slot machine.
Use ComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt;&gt; when an entity may carry several derived types (or several instances of the same derived type — see Slottable below) simultaneously, e.g. a unit stacking Poison and Silence at once.




                  WARNING



InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; binds a single pointer and cannot disambiguate. If an entity’s archetype ever carries more than one derived type of Base at once, a debug assert fires telling you to use ComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt;&gt; instead. This is checked per-chunk in debug builds only (compiled out under NDEBUG), so get it right in testing.


How Matching Works
Unlike All/Any/Without, an InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; requirement is not pre-baked into a bitset. DoesArchetypeMatch calls TypeRegistry::GetDerivedTypes(Base) fresh for every newly-created archetype, so a derived type introduced later — including by a hot-loaded plugin — is picked up automatically the first time some entity’s archetype actually carries it. There is no stale-cache window, because this resolution only ever runs against new archetypes, not every frame.
The read/write access sets used by the Processor dependency solver, however, are snapshotted from Base’s currently-known derived types at RegisterQuery time. A derived type registered after this query was built won’t retroactively create a dependency-solver conflict edge against another already-registered query — archetype matching stays fully dynamic, but the solver’s view of “what this query touches” is fixed at registration.
Slottable Derived Types
A derived type can itself be marked [[Reflect, Slottable]], letting a single entity carry several independent instances of it — e.g. multiple stacking poison ticks from different sources:
struct [[Reflect, Slottable]] StackingPoisonDebuff : DebuffComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(StackingPoisonDebuff)
    int StackPotency = 0;
};

EntityHandle Target = Library.CreateEntity();
Library.AddComponent&lt;StackingPoisonDebuff&gt;(Target, { {}, 10 }, &quot;PoisonFromArrow&quot;);
Library.AddComponent&lt;StackingPoisonDebuff&gt;(Target, { {}, 25 }, &quot;PoisonFromBlade&quot;);

// The span form collects BOTH slot instances as separate entries, same as it would
// collect two genuinely different derived types:
Library.ForEach(DebuffSpanQuery, [](ComponentSpan&lt;InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt;&gt; Debuffs)
{
    for(auto&amp; Entry : Debuffs) { /* one Entry per slot instance */ }
});
The single-bind InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; form treats multiple slots of the same Slottable derived type exactly like multiple different derived types — it trips the same “more than one match” assert described above, since it can only ever bind one pointer. Use the span form whenever stacking is possible.
Polymorphic Components
InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; does not require Base to be polymorphic, and — thanks to .As&lt;Derived&gt;() above — polymorphism is never required just to identify or downcast to the concrete type either. DebuffComponent in every example so far has no virtual functions; matching, binding, and downcasting are all driven entirely by TypeRegistry metadata and a reinterpret_cast/static_cast off the archetype column, valid because single, non-virtual inheritance guarantees Base sits at offset 0 of the concrete derived type.
Virtual functions are still fully supported when you want dispatch to live on the component itself rather than in a processor’s if/switch over the downcast — that’s purely a design choice, not something the binding machinery needs. Calling a virtual through the bound pointer dispatches normally to the concrete override — component storage always placement-news and destroys the exact concrete type (see TypeRegistry’s per-type Constructor/Destructor), so the vtable pointer is set up correctly. Take the same DebuffComponent hierarchy from above and add a virtual Tick:
struct DebuffComponent : Alchemy::CatalystComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(DebuffComponent)
    int SourceEntityID = 0;

    virtual ~DebuffComponent() = default;
    virtual void Tick(float DeltaTime) { }
};

struct PoisonDebuff : DebuffComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(PoisonDebuff)
    int DamagePerTick = 0;
    void Tick(float DeltaTime) override { /* apply DamagePerTick over time */ }
};

struct SilenceDebuff : DebuffComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(SilenceDebuff)
    float RemainingDuration = 0;
    void Tick(float DeltaTime) override { RemainingDuration -= DeltaTime; }
};

Library.ForEach(DebuffQuery, [](InheritsFrom&lt;DebuffComponent&gt; Debuff)
{
    Debuff-&gt;Tick(DeltaTime); // dispatches to PoisonDebuff::Tick or SilenceDebuff::Tick — real vtable dispatch
});



                  NOTE



Most InheritsFrom&lt;Base&gt; hierarchies in this engine are plain data with no vtable — use .As&lt;Derived&gt;() (see Downcasting to the Concrete Type above) when you need derived-only fields (see Components). Virtual functions are an option when you want dispatch to live on the component itself rather than in a processor, not a requirement of the feature.


Limitations

InheritsFrom&lt;T&gt; is only supported directly in BuildQuery&lt;&gt;’s required list (and inside ComponentSpan&lt;&gt;). It is not supported inside Optional&lt;&gt;, Bindless&lt;&gt;, Any&lt;&gt;, or Without&lt;&gt; — use InheritsFrom&lt;T&gt; in BuildQuery&lt;&gt; for presence, and Without&lt;&gt; with concrete derived types when you need to exclude a specific one.

Filtering by Markers and Sparse Components
Beyond the required / Any / Without sets over components, queries can filter by markers. A marker required for presence goes directly in the BuildQuery&lt;&gt; list; an excluded marker goes in Without&lt;&gt;:
BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent,
           IsSelected&gt;()              // marker — entity MUST have it
    .Without&lt;PendingDeath&gt;();         // marker — entity must NOT have it
Sparse components need no special query syntax. List one in BuildQuery&lt;&gt; like any other component and bind it in the lambda as a plain T&amp; — the query filters entities by sparse presence and resolves the data for you:
auto Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent, StunnedComponent&gt;());

Library.ForEach(Query, [](TransformComponent&amp; Transform, StunnedComponent&amp; Stun)
{
    // Stun is a sparse component, bound exactly like the archetype one
});
Archetype-resident requirements (components and archetype markers) are matched at archetype selection; sparse requirements (sparse components and sparse markers) are checked per-entity during iteration. The query reads identically either way — see Sparse Components and Tags and Markers.
Filtering by Tags
Markers answer presence (“does the entity have this flag?”). For hierarchical classification and boolean logic (AND/OR/NOT, parent/child matching) the engine uses the Tags system, and a query filters by it with .Tags(...). Pass a fully-built TagQuery — the builder accepts the tag predicate as an opaque value rather than mirroring the MatchAny/MatchAll/MatchNot vocabulary, so tag logic stays defined in one place.
auto Q = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent&gt;()
        .Tags(TagQuery::MatchAnyTags({ Weapon_Melee, Weapon_Ranged })));

Library.ForEach(Q, [](TransformComponent&amp; T)
{
    // Only entities whose TagComponent has a melee or ranged weapon tag
});
Tags() carries two implicit effects:

It requires TagComponent. Only entities that carry a TagComponent are visited — the predicate has nothing to evaluate otherwise.
It registers a read dependency on TagComponent, so the Processor dependency solver serializes correctly against any processor that writes tags. If you also need to write tags from the same processor, declare TagComponent (non-const) in BuildQuery&lt;&gt; explicitly; Tags() will not downgrade that to read-only.

Multiple .Tags() calls are ANDed:
BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent&gt;()
    .Tags(TagQuery::MatchTag(Weapon))                              // has a weapon
    .Tags(TagQuery::MatchNot(TagQuery::MatchTag(State_Dead)));     // and is not dead



                  NOTE



Tag predicates are evaluated per entity during iteration (the same slot as the sparse filter), so they are slower than archetype-level component/marker filters. The payoff is expressiveness: hierarchical matching and AND/OR/NOT composition that markers cannot express. Reach for a marker first; use a tag filter when you need hierarchy or logical composition. This applies uniformly across ForEach, ForEachParallel, ForEachFiltered, and ForEachParallelFiltered.


Filtered Query
The filtered query system provides two methods for processing a specific subset of entities rather than the entire world. The subset is an Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; — typically the result of a relation lookup such as GetChildrenEntities.
Serial (ForEachFiltered)
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Children = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent);

EntityQueryID Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;HealthComponent&gt;());

Library.ForEachFiltered(Children, Query, [](HealthComponent&amp; Health)
{
    Health.CurrentHealth -= DamageThisFrame;
});
Parallel (ForEachParallelFiltered)
Distributes the subset across worker threads. Returns a JobBuilder* so you can chain a Then() dependency after all batches complete. Returns nullptr if called outside a processor context (falls back to serial automatically).
// Must be called from inside a processor&#039;s Execute method (requires active JobBuilder)
if(JobBuilder* Builder = Context.Library.ForEachParallelFiltered(Children, Query,
    [](HealthComponent&amp; Health)
    {
        Health.CurrentHealth -= DamageThisFrame;
    }))
{
    // Optional: chain work that runs after all parallel batches finish
    Builder-&gt;Then(&quot;PostDamage&quot;, [this]() { NotifyDamageComplete(); });
}
The EntitiesPerJob parameter controls batch granularity (default: 64). From job system benchmarks, batches below ~50 entities cause thread-communication overhead to dominate — keep this value at 50 or above.
The query still acts as a filter in both methods — entities in the array that do not match it are skipped silently.
When to Use Filtered Queries
Filtered queries are the right choice when your logic only applies to a relation-defined subset of the world — a turret’s targets, a squad’s members, a room’s occupants.
Because filtered queries resolve each entity individually via a per-entity Records[] lookup, they have a higher per-entity cost than ForEach. Use the crossover formula to decide:
ForEachFiltered wins when:  subset_size  &lt;  world_size × (ForEach ns/entity / FilteredForEach ns/entity)

Measured benchmarks on this engine (Ryzen 9950x, 50k entity world):

























Methodns/entityNotesForEach~4 nsContiguous archetype sweep, no per-entity indirectionForEachFiltered~169 nsPer-entity Records[] lookup, column ptrs cached per chunkForEachParallelFiltered~179 nsSimilar to serial at small sizes; parallel overhead dominates below ~500 entities
This gives a crossover of roughly 3.3% of the world size. In a 50k world that is ~1,650 entities — if your subset is smaller than that, ForEachFiltered wins over a full sweep.
ForEachParallelFiltered matches serial performance at small subset sizes. It becomes worthwhile when per-entity work is heavy enough that parallel execution time exceeds the job dispatch overhead (~15 µs per thread handoff).
Caching the Subset
GetChildrenEntities is O(N) in the number of children. Calling it every frame on a large fan-out is expensive. Cache the result and re-query only when the hierarchy changes:
// Stored on the processor or relevant component
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; CachedChildren;
bool bHierarchyDirty = true;

// In the processor tick:
if(bHierarchyDirty)
{
    CachedChildren = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(RootNode);
    bHierarchyDirty = false;
}

Library.ForEachFiltered(CachedChildren, DamageQuery, [](HealthComponent&amp; Health) { ... });
How it Works (Advanced)
Archetype Caching
When a query is registered, the library scans all existing archetypes and caches those that match. When a new archetype is created at runtime, it is automatically checked against all active queries. This ensures that ForEach only touches relevant memory.
Element Mask Matching
Each archetype signature is a growable element mask — a bitset with one bit per archetype-resident type, indexed by a compact element index assigned on first use rather than by global type ID. Query matching is performed with fast bitwise AND/OR operations over these masks, letting the engine filter thousands of archetypes in microseconds. Because the mask grows as needed, there is no ceiling on how many component or marker types a project may define. See Element Masks and Identification.
Chunked Memory Awareness
The iteration helpers are aware of Catalyst’s 16KB Page architecture. They iterate chunk-by-chunk to maintain cache locality and handle page boundaries efficiently, especially during parallel execution.
See Also

Processor — processors register and execute queries
Relations — relation queries produce the filtered entity lists used with FilteredForEach
Jobs — ForEachParallel dispatches work through the job system

Catalyst/Processor/Observer.content:
Observer
Observers are specialized Processors that react to specific ECS events rather than running every frame. They are ideal for event-driven logic such as initializing physics when a component is added or playing a sound when an entity is destroyed.
Creating an Observer
To create an observer, inherit from IObserver. You must specify the component and the operation you are watching in the constructor.
class PhysicsInitializer : public IObserver
{
public:
    PhysicsInitializer()
    {
        // 1. What element are we watching?
        ObservedElement = TypeRegistry::GetType(RigidBody::StaticName());

        // 2. What event triggers us?
        ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::AddElement;
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Logic goes here
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;PhysicsInit&quot;; }
};
Watching Any Element
ObservedElement is a TypeInfo* and works for any Catalyst element, regardless of storage policy — archetype or sparse components, and archetype or sparse markers. A sparse change is not an archetype transition, but it raises the same AddElement / RemoveElement / CreateEntity / DestroyEntity events, so observing a sparse type reads identically to observing an archetype one.
To watch a virtual marker, resolve its fabricated type by name:
// Fires whenever the &quot;Stunned&quot; virtual marker is added to any entity
ObservedElement   = MarkerRegistry::GetOrCreate(&quot;Stunned&quot;, /*IsSparse*/ true);
ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::AddElement;
Event Types
Observers use the ObserverOperation enum to define triggers. You can use individual flags or convenient helper groups:

































FlagDescriptionAddElementA component was added to an existing entity.RemoveElementA component was removed from an entity.CreateEntityAn entity was born with this component (e.g. via Prefab).DestroyEntityAn entity with this component was destroyed.DisableComponentA component was disabled on an entity (entity migrated out of active queries).EnableComponentA disabled component was re-enabled on an entity.
Helper Groups

Add: Combines AddElement | CreateEntity. Use this to catch “birth” and “attachment” in one go.
Remove: Combines RemoveElement | DestroyEntity. Use this for all cleanup scenarios.
Toggle: Combines EnableComponent | DisableComponent. Use this to react to any visibility change.
All: Combines every possible operation.

Observing Toggle Events
Toggle Components fire DisableComponent and EnableComponent events that are distinct from structural add/remove. This lets systems react to streaming, LOD, or gameplay enable/disable cycles without confusing them with entity creation or destruction.
class [[Reflect]] StreamingObserver : public IObserver
{
public:
    StreamingObserver()
    {
        ObservedElement = TypeRegistry::GetType(MeshComponent::StaticName());

        // React to disable only — e.g. stop GPU uploads when mesh goes invisible
        ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::DisableComponent;

        // Or react to both:
        // ObservedOperation = ObserverOperation::Toggle;
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        for (EntityHandle Entity : *Context.AffectedEntities)
        {
            // Component data is still accessible via GetDisabledComponent while disabled
            MeshComponent* Mesh = Context.Library.GetDisabledComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(Entity);
            if (Mesh) ReleaseGPUResources(Mesh-&gt;MeshID);
        }
    }
};
DisableComponent and EnableComponent events are not fired by AddComponent or RemoveComponent — they are strictly for toggle transitions. An observer watching DisableComponent will never fire when an entity is destroyed.
Processing Changes
Observers operate on a Change List. The ProcessorContext provides access to the specific entities that triggered the event.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    // Method A: Iterate the specific entities that changed (Random Access)
    for (EntityHandle Entity : *Context.AffectedEntities)
    {
        RigidBody* Body = Context.Library.GetComponent&lt;RigidBody&gt;(Entity);
        Body-&gt;Initialize();
    }
}
Handling Large Change Lists
A common pitfall with observers is the cost of Random Memory Access. Accessing components for a scattered list of entities is slower than a sequential query.
If an observer is triggered by a massive batch (e.g., spawning 10,000 entities), you can run a query inside the observer instead of iterating the change list. This allows the engine to use SoA (Structure of Arrays) optimizations while still only running the logic when an event occurs.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    // Method B: Run a Query for cache efficiency (Sequential Access)
    // Useful if you expect many entities to trigger this at once.
    Context.Library.ForEach(MyOptimizedQuery, [](RigidBody&amp; Body) {
        Body.Initialize();
    });
}
Best Practices
Automatic Batching
The engine automatically batches events. If multiple entities trigger an event in one frame, your observer will run once with the combined list.
Parallel Dispatch
Observers are integrated into the engine graph and run on worker threads by default. They can run in parallel with other systems, ensuring that event-driven logic doesn’t stall the game thread.
See Also

Processor — Observers inherit from IObserver, a specialization of the processor concept
Entity Query — observers can run queries internally for cache efficiency on large change lists

Catalyst/Processor/Processor.content:
Processors are the logic units of the Alchemy ECS. While the Entity Library holds the data, Processors define how that data transforms over time. They are managed by the EntityLibrarySubsystem and executed automatically every frame.
Creating a Processor
To create logic, inherit from CatalystProcessor and implement Execute. The most common pattern is to iterate over entities using a EntityQuery.
class MovementProcessor : public CatalystProcessor
{
public:
    EntityQueryID Query;

    virtual void Initialize(EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) override
    {
        // Define what data we need once during startup
        auto Desc = BuildQuery&lt;PositionComponent, VelocityComponent&gt;();
        Query = Lib.RegisterQuery(Desc);

        // Declare the query to the dependency solver so it can serialize
        // this processor against others that touch the same components.
        RegisteredQueries.push_back(Desc);
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Optimized parallel iteration
        Context.Library.ForEachParallel(Query, [](PositionComponent&amp; Pos, const VelocityComponent&amp; Vel)
        {
            Pos.Value += Vel.Value * Context.DeltaTime;
        });
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;MovementProcessor&quot;; }
};
Configuration &amp; Ordering
Processors often depend on each other (e.g., Physics must run before Rendering). You declare ordering constraints in the constructor. The dependency solver resolves them into a concrete execution order every frame.
There are two ways to constrain ordering, plus a tie-breaker:
MovementProcessor()
{
    // 1. By execution GROUP (tag) — order against ALL processors in that group
    ExecuteAfterGroup.push_back(Tags::Input);
    ExecuteBeforeGroup.push_back(Tags::Physics);

    // 2. By specific processor NAME (string) — order against one exact processor
    ExecuteAfterProcessor.push_back(&quot;InputSamplingProcessor&quot;);

    // This processor&#039;s own group, for others to order against
    ExecutionGroup = Tags::GameLogic;

    // 3. Tie-breaker within the same dependency rank — higher runs first
    Priority = 0;
}






























FieldTypeMeaningExecuteBeforeGroup / ExecuteAfterGroupArray&lt;Tag&gt;Order relative to every processor whose ExecutionGroup matches the tag.ExecuteBeforeProcessor / ExecuteAfterProcessorArray&lt;String&gt;Order relative to one named processor (GetName() exact match).ExecutionGroupTagThe group this processor belongs to, so others can order against it by tag.Priorityint32Tie-breaker among processors at the same dependency rank. Higher runs first; negatives allowed.
The solver resolves name-based constraints first, then group-based constraints, then uses Priority to break remaining ties.
Thread Affinity
By default, Processors run on background worker threads (JobAffinity::Any). If you need to access main-thread-only APIs (like Windowing or OpenGL), you must specify it.
virtual JobAffinity GetAffinity() const override
{
    return JobAffinity::Main;
}
The Dependency Graph
Beyond the explicit ordering constraints above, the solver automatically serializes processors that would otherwise race on data. It does this from two declarations you populate in Initialize():

RegisteredQueries — an Array&lt;EntityQueryDescription&gt;. Push the same description you pass to RegisterQuery. The solver reads each query’s required-type list (where const means read-only — see [[Entity Query#how-const-maps-to-access|How const maps to access]]) to know which components the processor reads and writes. Two processors that write the same component are serialized; processors that only read it may run in parallel.
AccessedObjects — an Array&lt;WeakObjectPtr&lt;Object&gt;&gt;. List any external Object-derived instances (subsystems, managers, caches) the processor reads from or writes to. The solver serializes processors that share object access, closing the race that component analysis alone cannot see.

virtual void Initialize(EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) override
{
    auto Desc = BuildQuery&lt;PositionComponent, const VelocityComponent&gt;();
    Query = Lib.RegisterQuery(Desc);

    RegisteredQueries.push_back(Desc);              // component-level serialization
    AccessedObjects.push_back(SomeSubsystemPtr);    // object-level serialization
}



                  IMPORTANT



RegisterQuery does not populate RegisteredQueries for you — the two lists serve different purposes (one caches matching archetypes for iteration, the other informs the solver). If you register a query but forget to declare it in RegisteredQueries, the processor still runs correctly, but the solver is blind to that access and may schedule a concurrent writer against you. Always declare both.


Inline Processors
For cases where a full subclass is unnecessary — editor tooling, debug hooks, test fixtures, or short-lived runtime logic — use InlineProcessorBuilder to create a processor directly from lambdas.
struct MyState { EntityQueryID Query; };
auto State = std::make_shared&lt;MyState&gt;();

Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;HealthDrain&quot;)
        .OnInitialize([State](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib, CatalystProcessor* Proc)
        {
            auto Desc = BuildQuery&lt;HealthComponent&gt;();
            State-&gt;Query = Lib.RegisterQuery(Desc);
            Proc-&gt;RegisteredQueries.push_back(Desc);   // declare access to the solver
            Proc-&gt;ExecuteAfterGroup.push_back(Tags::Input);
            Proc-&gt;LibraryFilter = TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::GameWorld);
        })
        .OnExecute([State](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, CatalystProcessor* Proc)
        {
            Ctx.Library.ForEach(State-&gt;Query, [&amp;](HealthComponent&amp; HP)
            {
                HP.Value -= 1.0f * Ctx.DeltaTime;
            });
        })
);
Both callbacks receive an CatalystProcessor* pointing to the processor itself. All configuration — ExecuteBeforeGroup/ExecuteAfterGroup, ExecuteBeforeProcessor/ExecuteAfterProcessor, ExecutionGroup, Priority, LibraryFilter, RegisteredQueries, AccessedObjects — is set directly on that pointer inside OnInitialize. This means the builder never has to mirror CatalystProcessor’s fields; any new fields added to CatalystProcessor are automatically available with no changes to the builder.
State Between Callbacks
OnInitialize and OnExecute are separate lambdas, so they cannot share local variables directly. The standard pattern is a shared_ptr to a plain struct captured by both:
struct State { EntityQueryID Query; };
auto State = std::make_shared&lt;State&gt;();

// Both lambdas capture State by value (copies the shared_ptr, not the data)
.OnInitialize([State](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib, CatalystProcessor* Proc) { State-&gt;Query = ...; })
.OnExecute([State](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, CatalystProcessor* Proc) { /* use State-&gt;Query */ })

Important: Never capture stack variables by reference in either callback. Both lambdas outlive the call site — the builder is consumed immediately, but the processor continues running for the library’s lifetime.

Thread Affinity Without OnInitialize
If you need main-thread execution but have no initialization work, use WithAffinity on the builder — it is the one setting that must be known before Initialize runs:
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;UISync&quot;)
        .WithAffinity(JobAffinity::Main)
        .OnExecute([](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, CatalystProcessor* Proc) {
            // Safe to call ImGui / windowing APIs here
        })
);
Inline Observers and Signal Processors
The same builder can produce the specialized processor flavours, so observers and signal processors do not require a subclass either:
// An inline observer
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;PhysicsInit&quot;)
        .AsObserver(TypeRegistry::GetType(RigidBody::StaticName()), ObserverOperation::Add)
        .OnExecute([](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, CatalystProcessor* Proc) { /* ... */ })
);

// An inline signal processor
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;Respawn&quot;)
        .AsSignalProcessor(PlayerDied)
        .OnExecute([](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, CatalystProcessor* Proc) { /* ... */ })
);
.AsObserver(...) and .AsSignalProcessor(...) stamp in the flavour-specific configuration (the watched component/operation, or the signal tag) so OnInitialize never has to. See Observer and Signal Processor for the full behaviour of each.
When to Use a Named Processor Instead
Inline processors are a convenience, not a replacement. Prefer a named subclass when:

The processor will be reused across multiple libraries or modules
It carries significant state (many query IDs, configuration fields, caches)
It needs to be auto-registered via [[Reflect]] so it applies to all matching libraries automatically

Advanced Usage
The Active JobBuilder
During the execution of a Processor, Catalyst maintains a thread_local pointer to the active JobBuilder. This allows helper functions like ForEachParallel to automatically attach their sub-tasks to the current frame’s execution graph without explicit parameter passing.
Manual Job Dispatch
Sometimes you need raw control over the Job System. You can access the JobBuilder directly from the ProcessorContext to dispatch custom tasks.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    // Dispatch a custom job that depends on the processor&#039;s completion
    Context.Builder.Dispatch(&quot;ComplexTask&quot;, []() { ... });
}
Entity Command Buffers (ECB)
Processors are physically prohibited from making immediate structural changes (adding/removing components or destroying entities) to the EntityLibrary while executing. This ensures:

Thread Safety: Multiple processors can run in parallel without race conditions on memory layout.
Iterator Stability: Adding an entity won’t cause a query iteration to skip or repeat entities due to archetype transitions.

Instead, all structural changes are recorded into the EntityCommandBuffer provided by the ProcessorContext.
Core Commands
The ECB supports all standard ECS operations. These are recorded in O(1) time and played back at the end of the frame.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    Context.Library.ForEachParallel(Query, [&amp;](EntityHandle E, const HealthComponent&amp; Health)
    {
        if (Health.Value &lt;= 0)
        {
            // Record destruction - occurs after all processors finish
            Context.Commands.DestroyEntity(E);
        }
        else if (Health.Value &lt; 50)
        {
            // Record component addition
            Context.Commands.AddComponent&lt;ShieldComponent&gt;(E, { .Strength = 10 });
        }
    });
}
Toggle Commands
Toggle Components must also go through the ECB inside processors, since enabling or disabling a component is a structural change (archetype migration).
// Disable all slots of MeshComponent on this entity
Context.Commands.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E);

// Disable a specific slot by name
Context.Commands.DisableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Re-enable
Context.Commands.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E);
Context.Commands.EnableComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E, &quot;Weapon&quot;);

// Toggle (direction resolved at Playback time, not at record time)
Context.Commands.ToggleComponent&lt;MeshComponent&gt;(E);
The toggle direction for ToggleComponent is resolved when the command buffer plays back, not when you record it. This means the flip always reflects the entity’s actual state at the end of the frame rather than at the moment the processor ran.
Deferring Custom Logic
Beyond structural changes, you can defer arbitrary code execution using Enqueue. This is useful for logic that must run on the main thread or must happen after the world state has stabilized.
Context.Commands.Enqueue([=](EntityLibrary&amp; Lib) {
    // This lambda runs during playback on the main thread
    Log(&quot;Entity %d has been processed!&quot;, E.GetIndex());
});
Note on Captures: When using Enqueue, always capture by value ([=]). Capturing by reference is unsafe as the processor’s stack frame will be gone by the time the command buffer plays back.
Implementation Details

Linear Allocation: The ECB uses a page-based linear allocator (16KB pages). Recording a command is essentially a pointer increment, making it extremely fast.
Determinism: Commands are played back in the exact order they were recorded. If System A records a change before System B, that order is preserved during playback. - We have made the decision to sacrifice performance over determinism when it comes to the ECB. There are ways of batching commands or sorting them for better cache efficiency, or maybe even using the job system to multithread these commands, but in nearly every case when you’re working with the command buffer, you want it to be deterministic and on the game thread.
Playback Window: The EntityLibrarySubsystem automatically flushes the command buffer once all processors have reached a synchronization point (usually the end of the Update tick).

See Also

Entity Query — queries are defined and executed within processors
Observer — event-driven variant of a processor
Jobs — the job system processors dispatch parallel work to
Source/Engine/Catalyst/InlineProcessor.h - full InlineProcessorBuilder API

Catalyst/Processor/Signal-Processor.content:
Signal Processor
Signal Processors are specialized Processors that stay dormant until a signal is raised. A signal is identified by a Tag and may carry an optional list of entities and an optional data payload. They are ideal for decoupled, fire-and-forget events: “the player died”, “a wave spawned”, “reload a gun magazine” — logic that should run when something happens rather than every frame.
Creating a Signal Processor
To create a signal processor, inherit from ISignalProcessor and set the SignalTag it reacts to in the constructor.
DEFINE_TAG(PlayerDied);

class RespawnProcessor : public ISignalProcessor
{
public:
    RespawnProcessor()
    {
        // The tag that must be signalled for this processor to run
        SignalTag = PlayerDied;
    }

    virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        // Logic goes here — see &quot;Reading Signal Data&quot; below
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;Respawn&quot;; }
};
Inline Signal Processors
For tooling, tests, or short-lived logic, you can skip the subclass and use InlineProcessorBuilder with .AsSignalProcessor(Tag):
Library.AddProcessor(
    InlineProcessorBuilder(&quot;Respawn&quot;)
        .AsSignalProcessor(PlayerDied)
        .OnExecute([](const ProcessorContext&amp; Ctx, CatalystProcessor* Proc) {
            // Logic goes here
        })
);
See Inline Processors for the full builder API.
Raising a Signal
Signals are raised on the Entity Library via RaiseSignal. Both the entity list and the payload are optional, so there are four overloads:
// 1. Just a signal
Library.RaiseSignal(PlayerDied);

// 2. With a list of relevant entities
Library.RaiseSignal(PlayerDied, { DeadPlayerEntity });

// 3. With a data payload
Library.RaiseSignal(PlayerDied, InstancedStruct::Make(DeathInfo{ /* ... */ }));

// 4. With both entities and a payload
Library.RaiseSignal(PlayerDied, { DeadPlayerEntity }, InstancedStruct::Make(DeathInfo{ /* ... */ }));
Thread Safety
RaiseSignal is safe to call from any thread and is lock-free. Internally, signals are pushed onto a lock-free multi-producer queue (moodycamel::ConcurrentQueue), so gameplay code, job-system workers, and other subsystems can raise signals concurrently without locking and without needing access to an Entity Command Buffer. This is intentional: the wider engine is heavily multithreaded outside of Catalyst, and the ECB is not always reachable from where an event originates.
Reading Signal Data
Inside Execute, the ProcessorContext exposes the data of the signal that triggered this run through SignalData. Because both fields are optional, always check has_value() before using them.
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    if (!Context.SignalData.has_value()) return;
    const PendingSignal&amp; Signal = Context.SignalData.value();

    // The tag that was raised (useful if you ever share logic across tags)
    Tag Which = Signal.Signal;

    // Optional entities
    if (Signal.Entities.has_value())
    {
        for (EntityHandle Entity : Signal.Entities.value())
        {
            // ... react per entity ...
        }
    }
}
The entity list is also surfaced through Context.AffectedEntities (a pointer, nullptr when no entities were supplied), mirroring how Observers expose their change list.
Payloads
A payload is carried in an InstancedStruct. The payload type must be reflected ([[Reflect]]) so the type system can copy and identify it. Read it back with Get&lt;T&gt;(), which returns nullptr if the stored type does not match.
struct [[Reflect]] DeathInfo
{
    uint32_t Killer;
    String   Cause;
};

// Raising:
Library.RaiseSignal(PlayerDied, InstancedStruct::Make(DeathInfo{ KillerId, &quot;FellOffMap&quot; }));

// Reading:
virtual void Execute(const ProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
{
    if (!Context.SignalData.has_value()) return;
    const auto&amp; Signal = Context.SignalData.value();

    if (Signal.Payload.has_value())
    {
        const DeathInfo* Info = Signal.Payload-&gt;Get&lt;DeathInfo&gt;();
        if (Info)
        {
            Log(&quot;Player killed by {} ({})&quot;, Info-&gt;Killer, Info-&gt;Cause);
        }
    }
}
Dispatch Model
Signal processors fold into the dependency graph exactly like Observers. They participate in graph ordering every frame so they are correctly sequenced against the processors they depend on, but they only do work when a matching signal is pending.
Each frame, Update():

Drains the lock-free signal queue once into a per-frame snapshot.
Walks the dependency graph. When it reaches a signal processor, it dispatches that processor once for every snapshotted signal whose tag matches — so two RaiseSignal(PlayerDied) calls run the processor twice, each with its own entities/payload.
Clears the snapshot for the next frame.

Signals raised during a frame (e.g. by another processor) are picked up on the next frame, which keeps dispatch deterministic and avoids re-entrancy.
Best Practices
One Tag, Many Processors
Multiple signal processors can subscribe to the same tag. Raising it once dispatches all of them, ordered by their position in the dependency graph.
Parallel Dispatch
Like all graph nodes, signal processors run on worker threads by default and can execute in parallel with other systems. Record structural changes through the ProcessorContext’s command buffer rather than mutating the library directly.
Keep Payloads Small and Reflected
Payloads are copied into an InstancedStruct. Prefer small POD-like structs, and remember the type must be [[Reflect]] or Get&lt;T&gt;() will always return nullptr.
See Also

Processor — Signal Processors inherit from ISignalProcessor, a specialization of the processor concept
Observer — the other event-driven processor flavour; reacts to structural changes instead of explicit signals
Entity Library — owns RaiseSignal and drives signal dispatch during Update
Tags and Markers — signals are identified by Tags

Catalyst/Relations.content:
Relations
A Relation is a typed, directional link between two entities. It is implemented as a third relation entity that holds the two endpoint handles and a type marker — neither primary entity is modified.
Owner Entity ──[OwnsRelation]──► Target Entity
                    │
              Relation Entity
              ├─ RelationOwner { Owner }
              ├─ RelationTarget { Target }
              └─ OwnsRelation (marker)

This design keeps the primary entities structurally unchanged. The relation entity can also carry additional user-defined components, making it a first-class citizen in the ECS.
Terminology — “owner” and “target” are the generic terms. In a hierarchy context, the owner is the parent and the target is the child (e.g. AddRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent, Child)).

Defining a Relation Type
Derive from CatalystRelation and annotate with CATALYST_RELATION(). The configuration fields are set in the constructor and cached on the first AddRelation call for that type — construction cost is paid exactly once per type, not per call.
struct [[Reflect]] ChildOfRelation : CatalystRelation  
{  
    CATALYST_RELATION(ChildOfRelation)  

    REGISTER_ANNOTATIONS  
    {  
        ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::HiddenAnnotation());  
    }  

    ChildOfRelation()  
    {  
        UniqueParent = true; /**Children are only allowed to have one parent*/
        OnParentDestroyed = ERelationCleanupPolicy::DestroyRelation;  
        OnChildDestroyed  = ERelationCleanupPolicy::DestroyRelation;  
        WhenParentMoves  = ERelationMovePolicy::Follow;  
        WhenChildMoves = ERelationMovePolicy::Stay;  
    }  
};
Configuration Fields





















































FieldTypeDefaultDescriptionUniqueParentboolfalseEach child (target) may have at most one parent for this relation type. Adding a second replaces the first.UniqueChildboolfalseEach parent (owner) may have at most one child for this relation type. Adding a second replaces the first.MaxDepthint0If &gt; 0, prevents adding a relation that would exceed this depth in the graph. 0 = unlimited.OnParentDestroyedERelationCleanupPolicyDestroyRelationWhat happens when the parent (owner) entity is destroyed.OnChildDestroyedERelationCleanupPolicyDestroyRelationWhat happens when the child (target) entity is destroyed.WhenParentMovesERelationMovePolicyFollowWhat happens when the parent (owner) entity is moved to another libraryWhenChildMovesERelationMovePolicyFollowWhat happens when the child (target) entity is moved to another library
Cleanup Policies





















PolicyEffectDestroyRelationDestroys the relation entity only. Both primary entities survive.DestroyRelatedDestroys the relation entity and the other endpoint entity.DoNothingLeaves the relation entity alive with a dangling handle. The caller is responsible for cleanup.

Built-in Relations
ChildOfRelation
The standard parent/child hierarchy relation. Each entity may have at most one parent (UniqueParent = true). Destroying either endpoint destroys the relation entity; neither primary entity is destroyed.
EntityHandle Parent = Library.CreateEntity();
EntityHandle Child  = Library.CreateEntity();

Library.AddRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent, Child);

Working with Relations
Adding a Relation
EntityHandle RelationEntity = Library.AddRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent, Child);
Returns the relation entity handle. This can be used to attach additional data to the relation itself (see Attaching Data to Relations).
If UniqueParent = true and the owner already has a relation of this type, the existing relation is silently destroyed before the new one is created.
Removing a Relation
Library.RemoveRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent, Child);
Destroys the relation entity and removes it from both internal indexes. Both primary entities remain alive.
Checking for a Relation
bool bHasParent = Library.HasRelation&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent, Child);
Getting the Relation Entity Directly
EntityHandle RelEnt = Library.GetRelationEntity&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent, Child);
Useful for reading or writing components attached to the relation entity itself.

Querying Relations
All relation lookups are O(1) index operations.
Get All Children
Returns all owner entities that have a relation of this type pointing to the given target.
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Children = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent);
Get the Parent (Unique Relations)
For relation types with UniqueParent = true, each owner has at most one parent. Use GetParentEntity for a direct single-entity result.
EntityHandle Parent = Library.GetParentEntity&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Child);
Asserts that UniqueParent = true on the relation type.
Get All Parents (Non-Unique Relations)
For relation types without UniqueParent, an owner may have multiple relations of the same type.
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Parents = Library.GetParentEntities&lt;MyMultiRelation&gt;(Child);

Attaching Data to Relations
Because a relation is a real entity, you can add components to it just like any other entity. This allows storing metadata — such as edge weights in a graph, timestamps, or damage values in a combat relation — directly on the relation.
struct DamageRelation : Alchemy::CatalystRelation
{
    CATALYST_RELATION(DamageRelation)
};

struct DamageAmount : Alchemy::CatalystComponent
{
    CATALYST_COMPONENT(DamageAmount)
    float Value = 0.0f;
};

EntityHandle Rel = Library.AddRelation&lt;DamageRelation&gt;(Attacker, Defender);
Library.AddComponent&lt;DamageAmount&gt;(Rel, { .Value = 50.0f });

Processing Relation Subsets
When you need to run logic only on entities that are connected to a particular node, use FilteredForEach with the result of a relation query. See Entity Query — Filtered Query for full details and the performance crossover point.
Array&lt;EntityHandle&gt; Children = Library.GetChildrenEntities&lt;ChildOfRelation&gt;(Parent);
EntityQueryID Query = Library.RegisterQuery(BuildQuery&lt;HealthComponent&gt;());

Library.FilteredForEach(Children, Query, [](HealthComponent&amp; Health)
{
    Health.CurrentHealth -= DamageThisFrame;
});

Cleanup on Destruction
When Library.DestroyEntity(Entity) is called, the relation system runs before the entity is marked dead. This ensures index lookups remain valid during cleanup.
Parent destroyed: All relations where Entity is the owner (parent) are processed using OnParentDestroyed.
Child destroyed: All relations where Entity is the target (child) are processed using OnChildDestroyed.
Cleanup is recursive for DestroyRelated — if destroying a target also triggers a cascade, that cascade runs to completion before moving on.

Architectural Details (Advanced)
Why a Relation Entity?
The alternative (Flecs-style pair encoding) would mint a unique type ID for every (RelationType, TargetEntity) combination. Even with Catalyst’s growable element mask, that assigns a fresh archetype element index per pair and explodes the archetype count — a scene hierarchy with 1,000 parent nodes would create 1,000 one-off element types and shatter entities across as many archetypes. Modelling a relation as a real entity keeps the element space bounded to the relation types, not their instances, and adds no per-pair archetype churn.
Index Structure
EntityLibrary maintains two internal FlatMap indexes:

RelationsByOwner — maps (owner_index, relation_type_id) → array of relation entity handles
RelationsByTarget — maps (target_index, relation_type_id) → array of relation entity handles

Keys are packed as (entity_index &lt;&lt; 32 | type_id) into a uint64_t. Both indexes are updated atomically on every AddRelation, RemoveRelation, and DestroyEntity call.
Relation Config Caching
CatalystRelation-derived types are default-constructed exactly once (on the first AddRelation&lt;T&gt; call) to read their config. The result is stored in KnownRelationTypes and reused for all subsequent calls and during DestroyEntity cleanup.
See Also

Entity Query — FilteredForEach is used to process relation subsets
Components — relation entities can carry components like any other entity

Catalyst/Tags-and-Markers.content:
Alchemy’s ECS uses the word “tag” for its hierarchical tagging system, so what other ECS frameworks call “tags” (empty components used as flags) are called Markers here. This page covers both concepts and when to use each.
Markers
A marker is a data-less flag attached to an entity — Catalyst’s equivalent of what other ECS frameworks call a tag component. A marker carries no fields; only its presence or absence on an entity matters.
Like components, a marker declares a storage policy through the base struct it inherits, and uses the CATALYST_MARKER macro for its compile-time name:
// Archetype marker — presence is part of the entity&#039;s archetype.
struct [[Reflect]] PendingDeath : Alchemy::CatalystMarker
{
    CATALYST_MARKER(PendingDeath)
};

// Sparse marker — presence is stored in a side table, outside the archetype.
struct [[Reflect]] IsSelected : Alchemy::CatalystSparseMarker
{
    CATALYST_MARKER(IsSelected)
};
Archetype vs Sparse Markers
The base struct decides how the marker is stored and what adding or removing it costs:























Base structStored inAdd / remove costBest forCatalystMarkerthe entity’s archetype (a zero-size element)structural — migrates the entitystable state you filter on in bulkCatalystSparseMarkera side table keyed by entitynon-structural — no archetype changeflags toggled frequently at runtime
An archetype marker behaves like a zero-size component: it occupies a bit in the archetype’s element mask but stores no per-entity data, and adding or removing it migrates the entity to a new archetype. Because the flag is baked into the archetype, queries that require it are narrowed at archetype-selection time — the fastest possible filter — but each toggle pays an archetype migration.
A sparse marker records presence in a side table, so toggling it is a hash-table insert/erase with no archetype change. This makes sparse markers ideal for flags that flip many times per frame (IsSelected, IsHighlighted, Stunned). The cost is that a query requiring a sparse marker filters per-entity during iteration rather than at archetype selection.



                  NOTE



Reach for CatalystSparseMarker for anything toggled frequently, and CatalystMarker for stable classification you filter on in bulk. When in doubt, sparse is the safer default — it never fragments your archetypes.


Adding and Removing Markers
The API is identical regardless of storage policy — the base struct routes it:
// Direct library calls
Library.AddMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
Library.RemoveMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
bool bSelected = Library.HasMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);

// Via EntityCommandBuffer (deferred to playback)
CommandBuffer.AddMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
CommandBuffer.RemoveMarker&lt;IsSelected&gt;(Entity);
Querying by Marker
A required marker is listed directly in BuildQuery&lt;&gt;; an excluded marker goes in Without&lt;&gt; (string-named virtual markers use the WithMarker(&quot;Name&quot;) method):
BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent, HealthComponent,
           IsSelected&gt;()             // Entity MUST have this marker
    .Without&lt;PendingDeath&gt;();        // Entity must NOT have this marker
How the filter is applied depends on the marker’s storage policy — transparently, without changing how the query reads:

Archetype markers are folded into archetype selection: a required archetype marker is matched the same way a required component is, before iteration begins.
Sparse markers are checked per-entity during iteration against their side table.

Virtual (String-Named) Markers
Sometimes the set of markers isn’t known at compile time — for example tagging every item that belongs to a particular inventory, where the inventory id only exists at runtime. For this, Catalyst supports virtual markers identified by a string name rather than a C++ type:
// Defaults to sparse storage
Library.AddMarker(Entity, &quot;Inventory:42&quot;);
bool bInInventory = Library.HasMarker(Entity, &quot;Inventory:42&quot;);
Library.RemoveMarker(Entity, &quot;Inventory:42&quot;);

// Opt into archetype storage with the IsSparse flag
Library.AddMarker(Entity, &quot;Boss&quot;, /*IsSparse*/ false);
A virtual marker name is interned the first time it is used: Catalyst fabricates a TypeInfo for it behind the scenes, so from that point on it behaves exactly like a typed marker — including in queries:
auto Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;ItemComponent&gt;().WithMarker(&quot;Inventory:42&quot;));

Library.ForEach(Query, [](ItemComponent&amp; Item) { /* only inventory 42&#039;s items */ });
The storage policy is locked to the name on first use. A name first added as sparse is always sparse; passing a conflicting IsSparse for that name later is a programming error and is asserted against. Decide a naming scheme’s policy once and stick to it.
Virtual markers can also be recorded through the EntityCommandBuffer — the name bytes are copied into the buffer and the type is fabricated at playback, so recording stays thread-safe — and forwarded through EntityRef.
Internal Use: Relations
The Relation system uses a sparse presence marker internally to tag each relation entity with its relation type. This lets the library identify and clean up relations during entity destruction without storing any per-relation data.

Tags
The engine provides a TagComponent, which contains a TagCounterContainer (a reference-counted tag set). This is attached to entities that need complex hierarchical classification.
// Tags are attached via the engine Tags system — see [[Tags]]
Library.AddComponent&lt;TagComponent&gt;(Entity);
Library.GetComponent&lt;TagComponent&gt;(Entity)-&gt;Container.AddTag(Weapon_Melee_Sword);
TagComponent is typically added at entity construction and rarely removed. Adding or removing a tag within the component does not cause an archetype change — the TagComponent itself is the component; its contents are internal state.
Querying with Tags
Filter a query by tags with .Tags(...) on the query builder, passing a TagQuery. The predicate is evaluated per-entity against each entity’s TagComponent during iteration:
auto Query = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent&gt;()
        .Tags(TagQuery::MatchAnyTags({ Weapon_Melee, Weapon_Ranged })));

Library.ForEach(Query, [](TransformComponent&amp; T) { /* only weapon-tagged entities */ });
Tags() implicitly requires TagComponent (so only tagged entities are visited) and registers a read dependency on it; declare TagComponent non-const in BuildQuery&lt;&gt; if you also need to write tags. See Filtering by Tags for the full rules.
You can still evaluate a TagQuery by hand against any container when you need a check outside of iteration — build it from the static factories (TagQuery::MatchAnyTags, MatchTag, MatchAll, MatchAny, MatchNot) and call Matches:
TagQuery Query = TagQuery::MatchAnyTags({ Weapon_Melee, Weapon_Ranged });
if(Query.Matches(TagComp-&gt;Container)) { ... }
Because tag queries are evaluated per-entity (rather than per-archetype), they are slower than component or marker queries for bulk iteration. The trade-off is significantly more expressive power: hierarchical matching, logical combinators (AND, OR, NOT), and child-tag traversal.

Choosing Between Markers and Tags

































ScenarioUseBinary on/off state that changes at runtimeMarkerFiltering entities in bulk queriesMarkerClassifying entity types (tree, vehicle, NPC)TagHierarchical “is a child of” queriesTagComplex multi-condition logic (AND/OR/NOT)TagFrequently toggled per-frame flagsMarker
In general: reach for a marker first. Only use a tag when you need hierarchy or logical composition that markers can’t express.

See Also

Tags — the Tags system that this section references
Tag Query — building complex boolean queries over tag containers
Entity Query — archetype-based queries for component filtering

Crucible/Crucible.content:
Crucible
Crucible is a framework designed to test and validate the functionality of Alchemy Engine.
Creating tests
Crucible uses a “Behavior-Driven Development” (BDD) style for its tests. These types of tests are often called “spec testing”.
To implement a specification test, it’s fairly simple:
#if ALCHEMY_WITH_CRUCIBLE

BEGIN_SPEC(MySpec, &quot;Game.MyFeature&quot;)
    float Health;
    EntityHandle TestEntity;
END_SPEC(MySpec)

void MySpec::Define()
{
    Describe(&quot;Entity Management&quot;, [this]()
    {
        // Setup: Runs before every test below
        BeforeEach([this]()
        {
            Health = 100.0f;
            TestEntity = World-&gt;CreateEntity();
        });

        // Cleanup: Runs after every test below
        AfterEach([this]()
        {
            if (Health == 100)
            {
               LogError(&quot;Health is still 100.
                         Damage or healing did not apply&quot;);
            }
        });

        It(&quot;should take damage&quot;, [this]()
        {
            ApplyDamage(TestEntity, 10.0f);
            TestTrue(&quot;Health reduced&quot;, Health == 90.0f);
        });

        It(&quot;should heal&quot;, [this]()
        {
            // Health is reset to 100.0f here automatically!
            ApplyHeal(TestEntity, 10.0f);
            TestTrue(&quot;Health capped&quot;, Health == 100.0f);
        });
    });
}

#endif
Note the #if ALCHEMY_WITH_CRUCIBLE at the start and #endif at the end. These preprocessor macros will make sure that your tests never make it to release builds and makes sure this code never tries to compile whenever Crucible is not present.
The overall goal is to create very human-readable code by describing the logic that’s about to happen, then stating it does/should/could/would (whatever the context of the test is). You then have numerous test functions to evaluate if a result is as you expected.
For more examples, you can review the Engine/Source/Crucible/Tests folder, as it contains all tests for the engine. These tests can also be used to learn how to use certain frameworks by viewing them as “code samples”.
Running tests with breakpoints
Breakpoints won’t work on tests triggered by the frontend, since it’s running the raw .exe file.
To have breakpoints work, you must select AlchemyRunner in your IDE configuration and edit it. In Rider, you’ll see Program arguments and from there you can pass in the same arguments that the frontend is automating for you.
To run a test through these arguments, you can pass in -RunTest=”My.Test”. This can also take an array of tests, like so: -RunTest=”Test.One, Test.Two”. Now when you run AlchemyRunner, your breakpoints will trigger.
Recommendations

All tests should be found under a “Tests” folder. For the engine, this is mandatory. But for plugins and for your personal projects, there’s nothing stopping you from putting tests anywhere you want
Tests should try to be as fast as possible, instantaneous if possible. This is important for environments where you might have a lot of tests, or an environment where all tests are automatically triggered at some point (like once a week, once a day, per commit, etc).

See Also

Testing Guide — full guide for writing, running, and analyzing tests (especially for AI agents)
Profiler — Tracy integration for benchmark tests

Extension-Points.content:
Extension Points
Extension Points are points where you can insert custom code to be processed at a later time in the same callstack of the owner of the Extension Point’s processing logic.
The primary use case is ImGui. For example; if you want to add a button to the tools dropdown, you can get the tools extension point and directly add a button, all without referencing the tool section or even understanding where it is in the codebase.
Example
//Create an extension point
static ExtensionHandle ToolsHandle = ExtensionSubsystem::RegisterExtension(&quot;Tools&quot;);
//Placed inside your code, but executed by the tools menu.
ExtensionSubsystem::Push(TestHandle, []()
{
    ImGui::TextColored(ImVec4(0, 1, 0, 1), &quot;Extension Point Working!&quot;);
    ImGui::Button(&quot;Extension Button&quot;);
});
//The code found inside the tools menu
if (ImGui::Begin(&quot;Tools menu&quot;))
{
    ImGui::Text(&quot;Tools:&quot;);
    ImGui::Separator();
    /**Run the pushed lambda.
     * The pushed lambda may have been on a worker thread,
     * but we are now on the game thread. This is fine,
     * and is desired. This just means the pushed logic
     * will be executed on the game thread. */
    ExtensionSubsystem::Dispatch(TestHandle);
    ImGui::Separator();
}
ImGui::End();
The handle is optional. It’s also possible to use the name of the extension point.
Notes

This system might get replaced with Resonance as it shares very similar concepts

See Also

Resonance — the messaging system that overlaps conceptually with extension points
Sigil — the UI framework extension points primarily target

Input/Input-Handlers.content:
Input Handlers
An InputHandler is a step in the input pipeline that can read and optionally consume events before they reach the next processor. This is how editor tools intercept mouse drag, how ImGui claims keyboard focus, and how custom gameplay systems can suppress input in cutscenes.
Handler Chain
Handlers are sorted by Priority (highest first), with RunAfter&lt;T&gt; / RunBefore&lt;T&gt; for explicit ordering relative to specific types.
Priority 200+  →  Custom editor handlers (e.g. viewport camera drag)
Priority 100   →  UIInputHandler         (consumes events ImGui claims)
Priority   0   →  InputRouterHandler     (routes remaining to entities)

After each handler runs, consumed events are stripped before the next processor sees them. A handler at priority 100 can prevent priority 0 from ever seeing a keyboard event.
Built-in handlers
UIInputHandler
Runs at priority 100. Reads ImGui::GetIO().WantCaptureKeyboard and WantCaptureMouse each frame. When ImGui owns focus, keyboard events (DeviceID 0) and mouse button/scroll events (DeviceID 1) are consumed before they reach the router. Mouse move events are never consumed — the viewport still needs cursor position.
InputRouterHandler
Runs at priority 0. For every active EntityLibrary, queries all entities that have InputReceiverComponent + InputStateComponent + InputProfileComponent and resolves enabled profile slots into InputStateComponent.
Writing a Custom Handler
class CutsceneInputBlocker : public InputHandler
{
public:
    CutsceneInputBlocker()
    {
        Priority = 50; // Between UI (100) and router (0)
    }

    virtual void ProcessInput(Array&lt;InputEvent&gt;&amp; Events,
                              const InputProcessorContext&amp; Context) override
    {
        if(!bCutsceneActive) return;

        // Consume all keyboard and mouse events during cutscene
        for(InputEvent&amp; Ev : Events)
        {
            if(Ev.DeviceID == 0 || Ev.DeviceID == 1)
                Ev.Consume();
        }
    }

    virtual const char* GetName() const override { return &quot;CutsceneInputBlocker&quot;; }

    bool bCutsceneActive = false;
};
Register it with InputSubsystem:
auto* Blocker = new CutsceneInputBlocker();
Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;InputSubsystem&gt;()-&gt;RegisterHandler(Blocker);
Ordering with RunAfter / RunBefore
When priority numbers feel arbitrary, use explicit ordering constraints instead:
class MyToolProcessor : public InputHandler
{
public:
    MyToolProcessor()
    {
        Priority = 150;
        RunBefore&lt;UIInputProcessor&gt;();  // Must run before ImGui consumes events
    }
};
The subsystem performs a topological sort respecting both Priority and RunAfter/RunBefore constraints. Circular dependencies are detected and logged.
InputHandlerContext
Every processor receives a const InputHandlerContext&amp; with:

























FieldTypePurposeDeltaTimefloatFrame delta in secondsLibrariesconst Array&lt;EntityLibrary*&gt;&amp;All active entity librariesInputconst IInputStateProvider&amp;Raw key state queries (IsKeyDown, GetMouseDelta, etc.)
Event Types



































TypeDeviceIDNotesKeyPress0 (keyboard), 1 (mouse btn), 2+ (gamepad btn)Key/button went down this frameKeyReleasesameKey/button went up this frameMouseMove1Contains Ev.Axis = deltaMouseScroll1Contains Ev.Value = scroll amountGamepadAxis2+Contains Ev.Source = axis, Ev.Value = [-1, 1]
See Also

Input — overview of the full input pipeline
Input Profiles — how the InputRouterProcessor resolves profiles into state
Input State Component — the output that the input pipeline writes to

Instanced-Struct.content:
Instanced Struct
InstancedStruct is a type-erased container that can hold any struct registered with the Reflection system by value. It acts as a safe, polymorphic wrapper for data, similar to std::any but with reflection awareness and deep-copy semantics.
It is a foundational building block for systems that need to pass arbitrary data around, such as the Resonance messaging system.
Key Features

Type Erasure: Can hold any reflected struct.
Value Semantics: Handles deep copying and moving of the contained data using the TypeRegistry’s lifecycle functions.
Memory Management: Automatically manages the memory buffer for the contained struct.
Type Safety: Provides safe Get&lt;T&gt;() methods that check the stored type against the requested type.

Usage Guide
1. Registering a Struct
Any struct intended to be used with InstancedStruct must reflected.
struct [[Reflect]] MyData
{
    int ID;
    float Value;
};
2. Creating an InstancedStruct
You can create an InstancedStruct from any instance of a reflected type.
// Create from value (Copy)
MyData Data { 42, 3.14f };
InstancedStruct Wrapper = InstancedStruct::Make(Data);

// Create from r-value (Move)
InstancedStruct Wrapper2 = InstancedStruct::Make(MyData{ 100, 1.0f });
3. Accessing Data
To retrieve the data, you must know the type you expect. The accessor returns a pointer, or nullptr if the type mismatch.
// Const Access
const MyData* Ptr = Wrapper.Get&lt;MyData&gt;();
if(Ptr)
{
    Log(&quot;ID: {}&quot;, Ptr-&gt;ID);
}

// Mutable Access
MyData* MutablePtr = Wrapper.GetMutable&lt;MyData&gt;();
if(MutablePtr)
{
    MutablePtr-&gt;Value += 1.0f;
}
4. Lifecycle Management
InstancedStruct automatically calls the correct Destructor, Copy Constructor, and Move Constructor for the contained type.
{
    InstancedStruct Wrapper = InstancedStruct::Make(MyComplexType{});
    // MyComplexType is stored in Wrapper&#039;s internal buffer.
} 
// Wrapper goes out of scope -&gt; MyComplexType Destructor is called automatically.
API Reference

































MethodDescriptionMake(Value)Static helper to create an InstancedStruct from a value.Get&lt;T&gt;()Returns const T* to the data if types match, otherwise nullptr.GetMutable&lt;T&gt;()Returns T* to the data if types match, otherwise nullptr.IsValid()Returns true if the struct holds valid data.Reset()Destroys the contained data and frees memory.GetTypeInfo()Returns the TypeInfo* of the contained data.
See Also

Resonance — the primary consumer of InstancedStruct for message payloads

Jobs.content:
Job System
The Alchemy Job System is a high-performance threading engine designed to scale your game across every available CPU core. It allows the engine to perform thousands of small tasks simultaneously without the developer having to manage raw threads.

1. The Simple Version (Start Here)
What is a Job?
Think of a Job as a small “to-do” item. Instead of the main thread doing everything alone, it breaks the work into jobs and hands them to a group of “Worker Threads” who do the work in the background.
How to use it
To run code in the background, you use a JobBuilder.
// 1. Get the Job System
auto* Jobs = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;JobSubsystem&gt;();

// 2. Create a Builder to add tasks
JobBuilder Builder(*Jobs);

// 3. Dispatch a simple task
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;MySimpleTask&quot;, []() {
    Log(&quot;I am running in the background!&quot;);
});

2. The Power User Version (Chaining &amp; Groups)
Real games often need things to happen in a specific order. For example: “Calculate Physics, and THEN Update Animations.”
Chaining with .Then()
You can use the .Then() function to create a “Fence”. All jobs added before the .Then() must finish before the job inside the .Then() begins.
JobBuilder Builder(*Jobs);

// These two run in parallel (at the same time)
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;TaskA&quot;, []() { /* ... */ });
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;TaskB&quot;, []() { /* ... */ });

// This runs ONLY after TaskA and TaskB are both finished
Builder.Then(&quot;TaskC&quot;, []() {
    Log(&quot;A and B are done, now I can run!&quot;);
});
Processing Large Lists (ParallelFor)
If you have 10,000 entities, you don’t want to run 10,000 separate Dispatch calls. Instead, use ParallelFor to split the list into chunks automatically.
// Splits 1000 items into chunks and processes them across all CPU cores
Builder.ParallelFor(&quot;ProcessEntities&quot;, 1000, [](uint32_t index) {
    // Process item at &#039;index&#039;
});

3. The “God Mode” Version (Hierarchies &amp; Recursion)
The system is hierarchical. A job can spawn its own “Child Jobs”. The “Parent Job” is not considered finished until all of its children (and grandchildren) are 100% complete.
Builder.Dispatch(&quot;Grandparent&quot;, []() {
    auto Jobs = Engine::Get()-&gt;GetSubsystem&lt;JobSubsystem&gt;();
    JobBuilder ChildBuilder(*Jobs);

    // Spawn children
    ChildBuilder.ParallelFor(&quot;ChildTask&quot;, 100, [](int i) {
        // This is a grandchild!
    });

    // The &#039;Grandparent&#039; job effectively &#039;waits&#039; for all 100 children 
    // without actually blocking the thread.
});

4. For the nerds (Technical Deep Dive)
Our job system is HEAVILY inspired by CDPR’s amazing GDC talk. I highly recommend reading it.
Counter-Based Dependencies
Alchemy uses Atomic Counters instead of traditional Task Graphs.

Every job is assigned a WaitCounter and an AccumulateCounter.
A job stays in a “Waiting List” as long as its WaitCounter &gt; 0.
When a job finishes, it decrements its AccumulateCounter.
If a counter hits zero, the system automatically moves all jobs waiting on that counter into the “Ready Queue”.

Work-Stealing
The system uses a Multi-Level Work-Stealing Queue architecture:

LIFO Local Queue: Each worker has a private queue. It pushes/pops from the front (Last-In, First-Out) to keep data hot in the CPU cache.
FIFO Stealing: When a worker runs out of work, it looks at other workers’ queues and “steals” from the back (First-In, First-Out). This moves the “oldest” (and usually largest) tasks to other cores to balance the load.
Main Thread Help: When the main thread calls WaitForCounter(), it doesn’t sleep. It becomes a temporary worker, stealing jobs from the global pool until the work is done.

Thread Affinity
Some jobs (like Rendering or Window Input) require specific thread context.

Affinity::Any: Default. Can be stolen by any worker.
Affinity::Main: Hard-locked to the thread that initialized the engine.
Affinity::Worker: Locked to the background pool, preventing the main thread from stealing it.

Performance advice

Dispatching jobs has virtually 0 overhead and costs almost nothing to perform (range for starting and ending is usually between 1-7 micro seconds). But sending a task to another thread and managing the job graph and orchestrating the threads is slow (About 15 micro seconds). Whenever possible, you should use ParallelFor(), which can batch your jobs ChunkSize parameter). By batching your jobs, you can dramatically improve cache efficiency. - For example, on a Ryzen 9950x; - 100k jobs being dispatched in a normal for loop on average takes about 48ms - Due to how long it takes for a thread to receive a job, you usually don’t fully saturate the CPU. You’re essentially limited to just the speed of your threads communicating between each other and the time it takes to send jobs and how fast they can alert the job system that it’s finished and ready for a job new.
Batching 100k jobs takes about 1.6ms’s - Do note that you should not have ChunkSize too small. Otherwise, it becomes slower. Setting ChunkSize to 1 will actually cause this to skyrocket to 96ms’s. Typically there are diminishing returns beyond 50
Batching is the best way to fully saturate the CPU. Because you’re batching jobs together, it means the CPU has to do far less jumping back and forth between threads. A thread is given a list of jobs to perform and they can just go down the list with virtually 0 time between jobs.

Batching when done correctly can improve performance by up to 70% in some cases. For example, Catalyst queries automatically calculates the optimal entities-per-job ratio depending on how much component data can fit on the L1 cache. To better understand this, review the ComputeOptimalChunkSize() function.


If you have many different jobs, but still want to batch them, you can call BatchDispatch() (This is actually what ParallelFor() is doing).

See Also

Catalyst — Catalyst’s ForEachParallel is built on top of the job system
Profiler — Tracy integration for measuring job performance

Plugins.content:
Plugins
Plugins are independently-compiled DLLs that extend the engine or editor without modifying engine source. They are discovered automatically at startup and support hot reload during development.

Directory Structure
Plugins live in a Plugins/ directory either at the engine root (bundled plugins) or inside a project directory (project-specific plugins).
Plugins/
└── MyPlugin/
    ├── MyPlugin.alchemyplugin       ← manifest (required)
    ├── Binaries/
    │   └── MyPlugin.dll             ← compiled output (generated by build)
    └── Modules/
        └── MyPlugin/
            ├── MyPlugin.build.cs    ← build rules
            ├── MyPlugin.cpp
            └── MyPlugin.h

The Binaries/ folder is the output directory. The build system writes the DLL there automatically — do not put source files in it.

Manifest (.alchemyplugin)
Each plugin requires a JSON manifest in its root directory, named after the plugin folder.
{
    &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;,
    &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;1.0.0&quot;,
    &quot;EnabledByDefault&quot;: true,
    &quot;HotReloadable&quot;: true,
    &quot;Description&quot;: &quot;What this plugin does.&quot;,
    &quot;Modules&quot;: [
        { &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;, &quot;Type&quot;: &quot;Runtime&quot; }
    ]
}
Fields















































FieldTypeDefaultDescriptionNamestringrequiredPlugin identifier. Must match the folder name.VersionstringrequiredSemantic version string.EnabledByDefaultbooltrueWhether the plugin loads automatically. Projects can override this.HotReloadablebooltrueWhether the plugin supports hot reload. Set false for plugins that are unsafe to reload (e.g., plugins that modify global native state).Descriptionstring&quot;&quot;Human-readable description.ModulesarrayrequiredList of DLL modules this plugin contains.
Module Entry
{ &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;, &quot;Type&quot;: &quot;Runtime&quot; }




















FieldValuesDescriptionNamestringMust match the .build.cs filename and the Binaries/Name.dll output.TypeRuntime, Editor, RuntimeAndEditorControls when the module is loaded. Editor modules are skipped in non-editor builds.

Implementing a Plugin
Every plugin module exports a single factory function and implements the IPlugin interface.
IPlugin Interface
class IPlugin
{
public:
    virtual ~IPlugin() = default;

    virtual void OnLoad(PluginContext* Context) = 0;    // Called once when plugin is loaded
    virtual void OnUpdate(float DeltaTime) = 0;         // Called every frame
    virtual void OnUnload() = 0;                        // Called before plugin is unloaded

    // Optional: called before hot reload replaces this instance.
    // Use this to save any state you want to transfer to the new instance.
    virtual void OnHotReload(PluginContext* Context) {}
};
PluginContext
PluginContext is passed to OnLoad and OnHotReload. It provides access to engine singletons from inside the DLL boundary.
struct PluginContext
{
    void* ImGuiContext = nullptr;           // Cast to ImGuiContext* and pass to ImGui::SetCurrentContext
    void* TypeRegistryInstance = nullptr;   // Cast to TypeRegistry* if needed
    void* AnnotationRegistryInstance = nullptr;
    void* EngineInstance = nullptr;         // Cast to Engine* if needed
    const char* PluginDir = nullptr;        // Absolute path to the plugin root folder
};
Singletons are passed as void* because DLL boundaries do not share static state. You must set ImGui::SetCurrentContext in OnLoad if your plugin renders any ImGui.
Factory Function
Each module must export a CreatePlugin function:
extern &quot;C&quot; __declspec(dllexport) IPlugin* CreatePlugin()
{
    return new MyPluginImpl();
}
This is the only required export. The plugin manager calls it after loading the DLL.

Minimal Example
Plugins/MyPlugin/Modules/MyPlugin/MyPlugin.cpp
#include &quot;Engine/Plugins/IPlugin.h&quot;
#include &quot;Engine/Logging/Log.h&quot;
#include &lt;imgui_internal.h&gt;

using namespace Alchemy;

class MyPluginImpl : public IPlugin
{
public:
    void OnLoad(PluginContext* Context) override
    {
        ImGui::SetCurrentContext((ImGuiContext*)Context-&gt;ImGuiContext);
        Log(&quot;Loaded!&quot;);
    }

    void OnUpdate(float DeltaTime) override
    {
        ImGui::Begin(&quot;My Plugin&quot;);
        ImGui::Text(&quot;Hello from MyPlugin&quot;);
        ImGui::End();
    }

    void OnUnload() override
    {
        Log(&quot;Unloaded!&quot;);
    }
};

extern &quot;C&quot; __declspec(dllexport) IPlugin* CreatePlugin()
{
    return new MyPluginImpl();
}
Plugins/MyPlugin/Modules/MyPlugin/MyPlugin.build.cs
public class MyPluginRules : ModuleRules
{
    public MyPluginRules(BuildContext ctx) : base(ctx)
    {
    }
}
An empty build.cs is valid. The build system automatically links engine headers and the core DLL for plugin modules.
Plugins/MyPlugin/MyPlugin.alchemyplugin
{
    &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;,
    &quot;Version&quot;: &quot;1.0.0&quot;,
    &quot;EnabledByDefault&quot;: true,
    &quot;Modules&quot;: [
        { &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;MyPlugin&quot;, &quot;Type&quot;: &quot;Runtime&quot; }
    ]
}

Hot Reload
Plugins are hot-reloadable by default. When the engine detects that a plugin’s DLL has changed on disk, it automatically reloads it without restarting.
How It Works
Every frame, PluginManager::Tick() checks the last-write timestamp of each hot-reloadable plugin DLL against what it recorded at load time. If the timestamp has advanced:

The new DLL is shadow-copied to a temp file and loaded
If the copy fails (linker is still writing), reload is silently deferred to the next frame
Once loaded: OnHotReload() is called on the old instance, then OnUnload()
The old DLL is freed, the new instance takes over

This means you can rebuild the plugin DLL while the engine is running and changes appear automatically.
Shadow Copy
The engine never loads the DLL from Binaries/ directly. It copies it to a temp file first (%TEMP%/MyPlugin_HotReload_N.dll). This frees the original file for overwriting by the linker while the old copy keeps running.
Preserving State Across Reloads
Implement OnHotReload() to save any state before the instance is destroyed:
void OnHotReload(PluginContext* Context) override
{
    // Save any state you need before this instance is destroyed.
    // The new instance will start fresh with OnLoad().
    Log(&quot;[MyPlugin] About to be reloaded, saving state...&quot;);
}
Note: since the old and new instances are in different DLLs, you cannot transfer C++ objects directly. Serialize to a neutral format (e.g., write to a file or a global engine registry) if you need state continuity.
Opting Out
Set &quot;HotReloadable&quot;: false in the manifest to disable hot reload for a specific plugin. The plugin will only reload on engine restart.
{
    &quot;Name&quot;: &quot;CoreSystemPlugin&quot;,
    &quot;HotReloadable&quot;: false,
    ...
}
Use this for plugins that register global native hooks, modify memory allocators, or are otherwise unsafe to unload mid-session.
Project Overrides
A project can enable or disable specific plugins regardless of EnabledByDefault in the manifest. See the project descriptor documentation for the PluginOverrides field.

Discovery Paths
The plugin manager scans two directories on startup:

{EngineDir}/Plugins/ — engine-bundled plugins, available to all projects
{ProjectDir}/Plugins/ — project-specific plugins

Both directories are scanned at the same time. A project plugin with the same name as an engine plugin will load alongside it (they are not merged or deduplicated).
See Also

Build System — how plugin .build.cs files integrate into ABT and CMake
Hot Reloading — the hot reload mechanism plugins use
Annotations — plugins can register annotations externally during OnLoad

Resonance.content:
Resonance
Resonance is the high-performance, thread-agnostic messaging system in Alchemy Engine. It serves as the “nervous system” of the engine, allowing disparate systems (Physics, UI, Gameplay, AI) to communicate without tight coupling.
Resonance is built on top of the Job System and Tag System, making it both highly concurrent and expressively filterable.
Core Concepts
1. Frequency (Channels)
Messages are broadcast on Frequencies, which are represented by Tags (e.g., Game.Event.Explosion). Listeners subscribe to these frequencies using Tag Queries, allowing for powerful hierarchical matching (e.g., listening to Game.Event receives all child events).
2. Payload
Any struct registered with the TypeRegistry can be sent as a payload. Resonance uses a type-erased container (InstancedStruct) to safely copy and pass this data to listeners across threads.
3. Resonate (Broadcast)
“Resonating” is the act of sending a message. This is a non-blocking operation. The message is packaged into a Job and dispatched to the Job System for asynchronous execution.
4. Endpoints
By default, messages are global. Endpoints allow for private, targeted communication. An object (like a UI Window or Entity Component) can create a ResonanceEndpoint and listeners can bind specifically to it, ignoring global traffic.

Usage Guide
Defining a Payload
Any struct can be a payload. It just needs to be reflected.
struct [[Reflect]] DamagePayload
{
    float Amount;
    EntityHandle Instigator;
    Vector3 Location;
};
Listening to a Frequency
To receive messages, you “Listen” using a TagQuery. You also specify where you want the code to run (Main Thread vs Worker Thread) and its priority.
// 1. Define the filter (Listen to all &#039;Damage&#039; events)
TagQuery DamageFilter = TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::Game_Damage);

// 2. Subscribe
ResonanceListenerHandle Handle = ResonanceSubsystem::Listen(
    DamageFilter, 
    [](const ResonanceMessage&amp; Msg) 
    {
        // 3. Access Payload
        const auto* Data = Msg.GetPayload&lt;DamagePayload&gt;();
        if(Data)
        {
            Log(&quot;Took {} damage from Entity {}&quot;, Data-&gt;Amount, Data-&gt;Instigator.ID);
        }
    },
    JobAffinity::Worker, // Run this on any background worker thread
    JobPriority::High    // Prioritize this job
);
Stopping a Listener
When you no longer need updates, use the handle to stop listening.
ResonanceSubsystem::StopListening(Handle);
Resonating (Broadcasting)
Sending a message is simple and thread-safe.
// Create payload
DamagePayload Payload;
Payload.Amount = 50.0f;
Payload.Instigator = MyEntity;

// Broadcast globally on &#039;Game.Damage.Physical&#039;
ResonanceSubsystem::Resonate(Game_Damage_Physical, Payload);

Advanced: Endpoints (Targeted Messaging)
Endpoints are useful when you want to communicate with a specific instance of a system rather than the whole world. For example, a specific UI Window updating its content.
1. Creating an Endpoint
The owner of the private channel creates an endpoint.
class InventoryWindow
{
    ResonanceEndpoint MyEndpoint;

    void Init()
    {
        // Listen ONLY to messages sent to &#039;MyEndpoint&#039;
        ResonanceSubsystem::Listen(&amp;MyEndpoint, TagQuery::MatchTag(UI_Update), 
            [this](const ResonanceMessage&amp; Msg) {
                RefreshUI();
            }
        );
    }
};
2. Sending to an Endpoint
The sender must have access to the endpoint object.
void InventoryComponent::OnItemAdded()
{
    // Send specifically to the window&#039;s endpoint
    ResonanceSubsystem::Resonate(&amp;Window-&gt;MyEndpoint, Tags::UI_Update, ItemPayload{...});
}

Debugging
Resonance includes built-in debugging features to help trace message flow.

Source Tracking: Every message automatically captures the filename, function, and line number of the sender (Resonate call site).
Logging: The system logs registration and dispatch counts to the console.

Architecture &amp; Performance

Zero-Copy (Conceptually): The payload is wrapped in a std::shared_ptr when dispatched. If there are 100 listeners, the payload data is NOT copied 100 times; all listeners share read-only access to the same data.
Job System Integration: Resonance listeners are executed as individual Jobs. This allows the engine to automatically load-balance message processing across all available CPU cores.
Tag Query Optimization: Tag matching is highly optimized using the engine’s token-stream query evaluator.

See Also

Tags — tags define the frequencies (channels) messages are broadcast on
Tag Query — used to subscribe to frequency ranges
Jobs — listeners are dispatched as jobs
Instanced Struct — the payload container used by Resonance

Tags/Tag-Query.content:
Tag Query System
The Tag Query system provides a powerful and efficient way to check if a TagContainer or TagCounterContainer matches a specific set of criteria. It supports complex boolean logic (AND, OR, NOT) and hierarchical tag matching.
Overview
Queries are built using a fluent, nested syntax that compiles down to a compact Token Stream for high-performance evaluation.

Fast Execution: Uses a flat byte-code interpreter to avoid recursion and pointer chasing.
Hierarchical: All tag checks respect parent/child relationships (e.g., checking for Weapon matches Weapon.Sword).
Universal: Works on both TagContainer and TagCounterContainer.

Creating a Query
You construct queries using the static builder methods on the TagQuery class.
Basic Matchers
TagQuery::MatchTag(Tag)Matches if the container has the specific tag or any of its children.TagQuery::MatchAllTags({ A, B })Matches if the container has ALL of the specified tags.TagQuery::MatchAnyTags({ A, B })Matches if the container has AT LEAST ONE of the specified tags.TagQuery::MatchNoTags({ A, B })Matches if the container has NONE of the specified tags.
Logic Operators
TagQuery::MatchAll({ Q1, Q2 })AND: Matches only if all sub-queries match.TagQuery::MatchAny({ Q1, Q2 })OR: Matches if at least one sub-query matches.TagQuery::MatchNot(Q)NOT: Inverts the result of the sub-query.
Example
// Check if an entity has (Weapon OR Spell) AND NOT Dead
TagQuery CombatCapableQuery = TagQuery::MatchAll({
    // Condition 1: Must have offensive capability
    TagQuery::MatchAny({
        TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::Weapon),
        TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::Spell)
    }),

    // Condition 2: Must NOT be dead
    TagQuery::MatchNot(TagQuery::MatchTag(Tags::State_Dead))
});
Executing a Query
Once built, you can run the query against any container.
TagContainer MyContainer;
// ... fill container ...

if(CombatCapableQuery.Matches(MyContainer))
{
    // Logic for combat capable entities
}
Using with Entity Queries
A TagQuery can be handed directly to an Catalyst entity query with .Tags(...), which evaluates it per-entity against each entity’s TagComponent during iteration — no manual Matches call in the lambda:
auto Q = Library.RegisterQuery(
    BuildQuery&lt;TransformComponent&gt;()
        .Tags(TagQuery::MatchAnyTags({ Weapon_Melee, Weapon_Ranged })));
See Filtering by Tags for the requirement/dependency rules this implies.
Performance Tips

Reuse Queries: Build your TagQuery objects once (e.g., as static or member variables) and reuse them. Building a query involves memory allocation, but executing it is allocation-free. (When passed to .Tags(), the query is copied into the registered entity query once at registration — build cost is paid a single time.)
Prefer Bulk Matchers: Use MatchAnyTags({A, B}) instead of MatchAny({ MatchTag(A), MatchTag(B) }). The bulk matchers use optimized code paths.

See Also

Tags — the tag definitions and containers that queries operate on
Entity Query — filtering Catalyst entity queries by a TagQuery via .Tags()
Resonance — uses TagQuery to match message frequencies

Tags/Tags.content:
Tags are a hierarchical tagging system similar to Unreal Engine’s Gameplay Tags system, but we favour speed and power over convenience.
What is a tag?
In reality, a tag is just a number. When the engine is started, all defined tags are registered, sorted into a hierarchical tree and given a number. This number is used to compare tags, fetch parents/children, and simplifies many queries.
A tag being a simple number is what grants us tremendous speeds.

Comparing two tags is just a integer comparison, which means that checking for exact tags is blazing fast.
Performing a child check is just a Child.ID &gt;= Parent.Start &amp;&amp; Child.ID &lt;= Parent.End  check operation.
Performing a parent check is just a Parent.ID &lt;= Child.ID &amp;&amp; Parent.End &gt;= Child.ID check operation.

This means at worst, we are doing 3 to 4 machine instructions per tag.
Tag Container
A tag container is a simple array of tags that ensures only one copy of each tag is present.
Tag Counter Container
Identical to Tag Container, but it keeps a number for each tag. Adding a tag increments its counter by 1 and removing the tag decrements its counter by 1. The tag is only fully removed once the counter reaches 0.
Defining Tags
Alchemy provides 2 macros:

DEFINE_TAG() - This is the simple version

// Define simple tags
DEFINE_TAG(Weapon);
DEFINE_TAG(Weapon_Melee);
DEFINE_TAG(Weapon_Ranged);

DEFINE_TAG_ANNOTATED() - This allows you to create annotated tags.

// Define annotated tag
DEFINE_TAG_ANNOTATED(Weapon_Melee_Sword, {
    ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::EditorIcon{&quot;Icons/Sword.png&quot;});
});

DEFINE_TAG_ANNOTATED(Status_Stunned, {
    ADD_ANNOTATION(Alchemy::EditorIcon{&quot;Icons/Stun.png&quot;});
});
Tag Component
Entities can have tags applied to them via the TagComponent, then queried through it.
This tag system is not the same as other ECS’s tags. In other ECS’s, like Flecs, a tag is just an empty component. For Alchemy, a tag is much slower, but far more powerful.

The speed: In Alchemy, we can’t narrow down an archetype via tags. Instead, we have to process each entity and perform the tag query. Although, since we have heavily optimized the tag query system, this is still blazing fast.
The power: Since we are using hierarchical tags, we can fetch all entities with complex tag queries. For example; getting all entities who have a tag that’s a child of Entity.Type.Tree. This will return all entities that have tags such as Entity.Type.Tree.Pine and Entity.Type.Tree.Burch.

Tag Entities
//Not yet implemented
Entities can be created and tied to a specific tag on another entities tag. This in essence allows you to add any data you want onto a tag on an entity via components.
This is particularly useful for temporary tags. You can give a tag entity a Lifetime component to have the tag be removed once the tag entity dies.
See Also

Tag Query — building complex boolean queries over tag containers
Resonance — uses tags as message frequencies
Tags and Markers — how tags and markers interact with the ECS
